<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Four DKB Officials Arrested as Racketeer Scandal Grows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Four officials of a top Japanese
commercial bank were arrested today for involvement in a widening
corporate racketeering scandal that also involves the country's
biggest brokerage.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors said the four officials of Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank Ltd
(DKB) were arrested on suspicion of violating the Commercial Code
by allegedly loaning 11.78 billion yen (101 million U.S. dollars)
to a racketeer.
</P>
<P>
The racketeer, Ryuichi Koike, is the leading member of a band
of racketeers known as "sokaiya" who extort money from companies
by threatening to ask embarrassing and sensitive questions about
their business activities at shareholder meetings.
</P>
<P>
The country's top brokerage, Nomura Securities Co. Ltd, has
been involved in the pay-off scandal to buy Koike's silence at
shareholder meetings.
</P>
<P>
"Sokaiya" buy stakes in firms to gain admission to the annual
shareholder meetings. Their activities were outlawed in 1982 but
the practice flourished nevertheless.
</P>
<P>
The four arrested DKB officials were all linked to the bank's
general affairs department, which traditionally handles dealings
with "sokaiya."
</P>
<P>
They included former director Hiroshi Inotsume and current
general manager Tatsuo Shibuya.
</P>
<P>
The arrests were made a day after prosecutors linked Nomura
itself to the scandal, suggesting the company has violated
securities laws by compensating Koike's younger brother for
trading losses.
</P>
<P>
Former Nomura President Hideo Sakamaki and two former managing
directors of the brokerage have been arrested for conspiring to
give cash to Koike. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
