<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Welcomes US Appointment of New Emissary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government welcomed
today the appointment of Richard Holbrooke as new U.S.
Presidential Emissary for Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
"Bearing in mind U.S. assurances for active, substantial and
dynamic presence in direct talks and for support to U.N. efforts
toward a Cyprus settlement, we expressed our satisfaction with
Holbrooke's appointment," Government Spokesman Manolis
Christofides told reporters at his daily press briefing here.
</P>
<P>
U.S. State Department Spokesman Nicholas Burns officially
announced Wednesday the appointment of Richard Holbrooke, the
former assistant secretary of state for European affairs, as
President Bill Clinton's emissary for Cyprus, to replace Richard
Beattie, the emissary in Clinton's previous term of office.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke, known for his tough bargaining style, achieved his
fame by negotiating the 1995 Dayton peace agreement which ended
a 43-month civil war in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman pointed out that the Cypriot government hopes
for a just solution to the Cyprus problem which will be in line
with what he termed as universal values the U.N. and the U.S. have
pledged to abide by.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Cypriot Foreign Minister Ioannis Kasoulides, who is
currently in Washington to have a meeting with U.S. Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright, also voiced his welcome to the
appointment.
</P>
<P>
He said today that the appointment "sends messages regarding
the determination with which the U.S. government will work
towards a solution to the Cyprus issue."
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that Holbrooke's appointment came just a
month before the U.N.-sponsored direct negotiations between the
Greek and Turkish Cypriot sides begin in New York.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus issue has remained unsolved since 1974 when the
island was divided after Turkish troops occupied its northern
third in the wake of an Athens-backed coup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
