<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Launches Environmental Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The Ethiopian government today
launched its environmental policy to mark this year's World
Environment Day.
</P>
<P>
The environmental policy has an overall objective to improve and
enhance the health and quality of life of all Ethiopians and to
promote sustainable social and economic development through the
sound management and use of natural, man-made and cultural resources.
</P>
<P>
It also seeks to ensure that the benefits from the exploitation of
non-renewable resources are extended as far into the future as can
be managed, and minimize the negative impacts of their exploitation.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the launching ceremony here, Minister of Agriculture
Seifu Ketama said the environmental policy of Ethiopia is a
derivation of part of the conservation strategy of Ethiopia and is
aimed to guide all environment related activities which are
undertaken or must be undertaken by the environmental protection
authority and the other sectors.
</P>
<P>
The formulation of the conservation strategy of Ethiopia was
conducted in three phases following the signing of the first project
agreement between the government of Ethiopia and the World
Conservation Union, the minister added.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia loses 80,000 to 200,000 hectares of forest annually.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
