<DOCNO> XIE19970606.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraqi Paper Attacks U.S. Military Presence in Gulf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 5 (Xinhua) -- An Iraqi newspaper here today
strongly criticized the continuation of the U.S. military
presence in the Gulf region "under various pretexts."
</P>
<P>
In an editorial, Ath-thawra, organ of the ruling Arab Ba'th
Socialist Party, said the gulf people are well aware that the
presence of the U.S. forces, with their bases, troops and
maneuvers on their land and at sea, violates their countries'
sovereignty and constitutes a direct pressure on their political
decision-making.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has stationed 25,000 soldiers, 80 fighters and 35
warships in the Gulf, the paper said, claiming that about 40
billion dollars is used to cover the costs of their presence.
</P>
<P>
The real reason behind the U.S. presence here is not, as the
Americans claim, that they provide protection for the Gulf states
from an Iraqi threat first and an Iranian threat second.
</P>
<P>
It aims to achieve political and financial purposes represented
in the U.S. desire to impose hegemony over the region's strategic
oil resources now and in the future, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The Gulf states have to solve their problems by themselves and
in their own special way, said the paper, adding that the
Americans are "not but strangers who hate the Arabs and Islam and
hate to see the Arabs unified."
</P>
<P>
Seven years ago, Iraq troops were defeated and driven out of
Kuwait after their nearly six-month occupation, by U.S-led allied
forces in the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has since maintained a large number of forces in the
region to carry out its so-called "dual-containment" policy in
order, as it said, to protect the Gulf states such as Kuwait and
Saudi Arabia from a potential threat posed by Iraq and to deter
Iran. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
