<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Deems Upcoming Direct Talks Important </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government considered
the forthcoming direct talks between the Greek and Turkish
Cypriots particularly important, a government spokesman said here
today.
</P>
<P>
At his daily press briefing, spokesman Manolis Christofides
said the talks have been endorsed by the permanent member of the
U.N. Security Council, and "this is the first time that so many
have shown such an interest simultaneously in a Cyprus solution."
</P>
<P>
According to the spokesman, representatives of Britain,
France, Russian and the United States will be present at the
face-to-face negotiations between President Glafcos Clerides and
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash, scheduled for July near
the U.N. headquarters of New York.
</P>
<P>
China, he said, has yet to nominate its representative but it
has shown interest in the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
Christofides expected progress to be achieved in the direct
talks, saying that this expectation is boosted by the action of
states that are keen on a Cyprus settlement.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Cypriot Foreign Minister Ioannis Kasoulides has
expressed the country's political will to take part in the
U.N.-proposed direct talks in a positive and constructive way in
order to achieve the island's reunification the soonest possible.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a meeting Wednesday night in Washington, Kasoulides
said "we must show the world that we want our country to be
reunited, that we want reconciliation in Cyprus, that we want to
live in peace with our fellow citizens, the Turkish Cypriots, and
that the future is common for all Cypriots in our country."
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that if Greek and Turkish Cypriots were left
alone without what he called foreign intervention and the
presence of Turkish occupation troops, they will live peacefully
and "we can have a bright future for everybody on our island."
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides said "time is running against us and therefore, we
want a Cyprus solution to come as quickly as possible."
</P>
<P>
He assured that the Greek Cypriot side will attend the July
direct talks near New York "with an open mind" and with "a
spirit ready to negotiate in a positive and constructive way."
</P>
<P>
"If the other side (of Turkish Cypriots) comes with a similar
political will and with a similar spirit then we will be able to
celebrate the withdrawal of the Turkish occupation army, the
restoration of the basic freedoms, the reunification of our
country, the reconciliation of all Cypriots and a peaceful
future for our children in our beloved island," the minister
said.
</P>
<P>
This eastern Mediterranean island has been divided since 1974
when Turkish troops occupied the northern third of the island in
the wake of a short-lived coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Peace efforts made by the U.N. and international community for
the past 23 years have achieved no tangible results for a solution
to the Cyprus' problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
