<HEADLINE> Portuguese-Speaking African States Discuss </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAUNDA,June 5 (Xinhau)-- Representatives from five
Portuguese-speaking African countries today began a 14-day
meeting to discuss ways to promote external trade and investment.
</P>
<P>
Representative of Angola, Sao Tome and Principe, Mozambique
amd Cape Verde attended today's opening session and delegate of
Guinea-Bissau has not yet arrived.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the first meeting of the working team on the
external trade and investment promotion plan, Angolan
Vice-Minister of Trade Cruz Neto said that representatives from
the five countries will exchange their experience in trade and
investment and formulate new trade strategies in order to face
challenges in international trade.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, the participants will discuss and revise their
laws of external trade and investment to meet the regional and
wold economic situation. They will also discuss
foreign exchange, finance and tax levy.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, the five countries will formulate their common
strategies which will govern their relations with various
partners in trade and investment to ensure the countries competitive
in world trade.
</P>
<P>
The external trade and investment promotion plan, which will
be financed by the European Union, will begin its implementation
in July this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
