<HEADLINE> Blair to Urge Germany to Go Ahead With Eurofighter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 5 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
has promised to urge German Chancellor Helmut Kohl to sign up to
the final phases of the Eurofighter program during his brief visit
to Germany Friday.
</P>
<P>
Blair was quoted by local press reports as saying Wednesday
night that the 40-billion-pound (about 65 billion U.S. dollar)
project was important for British defense and jobs.
</P>
<P>
"We will be doing everything we can to see the project out,"
Blair said.
</P>
<P>
Defense experts predict that the four-nation European fighter
project, involving Germany, Britain, Spain and Italy, is expected
to create some 100,000 jobs in Britain.
</P>
<P>
The four countries were supposed to sign the production
investment agreement which would allow each of the four nations to
build the production lines last year, but the German government,
which needs budget cuts in an effort to qualify for the single
European currency, has demanded delays in funding the program.
</P>
<P>
In other developments, German Defense Minister Volker Ruehe
held talks with visiting British Defense Secretary George
Robertson in Bonn Wednesday to exchange views on the Eurofighter
program, but no breakthrough has so far emerged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
