<HEADLINE> Basic Science Teaching to Be Improved in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 5 (Xinhua) --The Tanzanian government is
determined to improve the teaching of basic science in
primary and secondary schools.
</P>
<P>
Receving the visiting Executive Director of the Third World
Academy of Sciences, Mohamed Hassan this morning, Mkapa noted
that the deteoration of science education in Africa was mainly
due to the prevailing economic situation, whereby most national
budgets in the continent fail to give adequate support for the
education sector.
</P>
<P>
"In Tanzania a program is underway to resume the provision of
practical science classes in full as soon as possible in order to
meet the demands of science and technology in the 21st century,"
Mkapa said.
</P>
<P>
According to a press statement issued by the State House,
Mkapa said that the provision of basic science education in
primary and secondary schools, which should be seen as a lead to
the training of innovative and inventive scientists, needed
international co-operation and support.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the president hailed the Third World Academy of
Sciences, which was created under the initiative of the
South-South co-operation, for its efforts to finance the
development of scientific work in the third world.
</P>
<P>
In this respect, Mkapa called for an African regional special
consideration in the imparting of science and technology as the
continent lagged behind Latin American and Asian states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
