<HEADLINE> Kinkel Urges Strengthened US-Europe Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 5 (Xinhua) -- German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel
today called for strengthened ties between Europe and the Unites
States in a speech marking the 50th anniversary of the Marshall
Plan that had helped rebuild the post-war Europe.
</P>
<P>
"The reconstruction of the European house must be in step with
the strengthening of the trans-Atlantic bridge," said Kinkel at
the celebration ceremony in Bonn.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel said concerns over a steady erosion of the US-Europe
partnership had to be taken seriously. "For Europeans, there is
only one way to maintain the US interest in Europe. It means major
changes... to make it a competitive and decision-making player and
partner of America on the world stage," he added.
</P>
<P>
He also said that it could not be left to the Unites States to
solve problems for Europeans.
</P>
<P>
Attending the ceremony were also German President Roman Herzog,
Vice President of the EU Commission Sir Leon Brittan and
diplomats.
</P>
<P>
Former US Secretary of State George Marshall initiated the
reconstruction plan for Europe after World War II.
</P>
<P>
German Economics Minister Guenter Rexrodt earlier said the
Marshall Plan economic aid of 1.5 billion US dollars granted to
post-war Germany helped integrate Germany into the Western
community. 
</P>
</TEXT>
