<HEADLINE> Poll Indicates Irish Opposition Likely to Win Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The voters in the Republic of
Ireland will cast their ballots in the general election to be held
Friday and the latest opinion poll indicated the opposition
coalition is likely to win the election.
</P>
<P>
The survey in today's Irish Independent newspaper showed that
the center-right opposition alliance, including the country's
largest political Fianna Fail party and the Progressive Democrats,
gained support of 49 percent, nine points ahead of the ruling
coalition.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister John Bruton's three-party ruling alliance, which
is consistently trailing the opposition in the three-week election
campaign, is battling to win over the 14 percent of voters who are
still undecided over their choice in a last-ditch effort to turn
the tables.
</P>
<P>
The survey also revealed that although 53 percent of those
polled expressed satisfaction over the current coalition
government, they still wanted to have a change of government.
</P>
<P>
"The poll underlines a startling reality -- a successful
government well regarded by more than half of voters stares defeat
in the face," an analyst said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
