<HEADLINE> Ex-CIA Spy Sentenced to 23 Years in Jail in US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 5 (Xinhua) -- U.S. double-spy Harold Nicholson
was sentenced today in Alexandria, Virginia, to 23 years and seven
months imprisonment for selling classified information to Russia.
</P>
<P>
On March 3, Nicholson, 46, pleaded guilty to conspiracy to
commit espionage by selling the names and positions of a large
number of U.S. intelligence officers to Moscow.
</P>
<P>
"I won't ask for the forgiveness of my colleagues and
countrymen for I know they cannot give it," Nicholson said before
the sentencing today.
</P>
<P>
He served as the Central Intelligence Agency (CIA) station
chief in Romania from 1990 to 1992 before becoming deputy chief of
station and operations in Malaysia. From 1994 to 1996, Nicholson
served as a trainer for CIA recruits.
</P>
<P>
Nicholson confessed to having started spying for Moscow in June
1994 and admitted collecting 300,000 U.S. dollars from the
Russians.
</P>
<P>
In November 1996, Nicholson was arrested at Dulles
International Airport near Washington when he was carrying film
and a computer of classified information to pass on the Russian
agents in Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors said that Nicholson has "fully cooperated" and
"substantially" helped the Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI)
and CIA in the investigation.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, they said, 23 years and seven months imprisonment is
"a sufficient and appropriate punishment" for his crime. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
