<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOMOG Chief Sees No Need to Evacuate Nigerians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 5 (Xinhua) -- ECOMOG Force Commander Major-General
Victor Malu said here today that there was no need to panic over
the non-evacuation of Nigerians in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
The situation had not come to that, said Malu who arrived from
the Liberian capital Monrovia to confer with General Sani Abacha,
Nigeria's head of state and chairman of the Economic Community of
West African States.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the rebel leader in Sierra Leone was very
much aware of what the Nigeria-led ECOMOG troops could do and that
was why he called for a ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
Malu was referring to Major Johnny Koromah, chairman of the
ruling Armed Forces Revolutionary Council set up by soldiers
after the coup on May 25 that toppled Sierra Leone's elected
government led by President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
Major Koromah has called for a ceasefire under the military
intervention of ECOMOG and political pressure from the
international community for the restoration of Kabbah's
government.
</P>
<P>
However, Malu said that ECOMOG's planned operation to flush
out the soldiers had not started.
</P>
<P>
"We had some skirmishes which we undertook just to protect
ourselves," he said, quoted by the News Agency of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
"We were fired upon and we had to return fire and in the
course of that we sustained some casualties," he added.
</P>
<P>
He noted that ECOMOG's strong stance and mandate in the
operation had convinced the rebels of its resolve to sort out
issues militarily if it became necessary.
</P>
<P>
On the movement of troops from Liberia to Sierra Leone, Malu
said: "I can't afford to substantially deploy my men to Sierra
Leone, very few and essential few have been moved to Sierra
Leone."
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian military has said earlier that some ECOMOG troops
had been sent from Liberia to Sierra Leone but it would not
create loopholes in Liberia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
