<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt: Jerusalem Issue Open to Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa
today reaffirmed that the Jerusalem issue should be settled in
the Palestinian-Israeli final talks in line with signed
agreements.
</P>
<P>
Moussa made the statement when commenting on a peace plan
presented Wednesday by Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu
for a final settlement with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
"It has been agreed that the issue of Jerusalem is negotiable,
but any talks on this holy city by any party, if clashing with
signed agreements and relevant UN resolutions, will adversely
affect the final phase peace talks," Moussa said.
</P>
<P>
The plan Netanyahu presented to the inner cabinet for
discussions envisioned retaining Israeli control over the
strategic borders, Greater Jerusalem, settlements, water
resources and key roads in the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
The status of Jerusalem, a focus in the current peace crisis,
has been agreed to be kept intact until the talks on a final
Palestinian-Israeli peace deal.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt's stand on the issue is clear, firm and unchanged," said
Moussa, who warned that any attempt to temper with Jerusalem's
current features will be detrimental to the final negotiations
that are yet to resume.
</P>
<P>
"Negotiation is a must on the status of Al Quds (Jerusalem)
and any current procedures in the city shall not have to create
any status quo that clashes with international legitimacy and
renders inevitable negotiations on it meaningless," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace talks have deadlocked since
March when Israel began the construction of a new Jewish
settlement on disputed land in Arab East Jerusalem despite
international outcry.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said it was to early to speak of any expected
breakthrough in reviving the paralyzed peace process.
</P>
<P>
He was critical of Netanyahu's plan, which he branded as
extremely harmful to any initiative or any action to settle
problems in the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian National Authority (PNA) hopes to establish an
independent state as East Jerusalem as its capital in the final
arrangements.
</P>
<P>
The current hardline Israeli government has ruled out the
redivision of Jerusalem and existence of a Palestinian state
alongside Israel.
</P>
<P>
The PNA President Yasser Arafat has denounced the plan as
violating the Israeli-Palestinian peace agreements and dealing
another blow to Mideast peace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
