<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Computer Printer Sales to Slow Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The market for computer printers
is slowing despite of aggressive price cuts by major printer
makers.
</P>
<P>
In the consumer market, unit sales are expected to rise 15
percent in 1997 as against 31 percent last year, according to
Dataquest, a major market researcher of the U.S.
</P>
<P>
Revenue will be up 8 percent as against 16 percent a year ago.
In the corporate market, unit sales are expected to dip slightly,
while revenue will decline 13 percent, compared to last year's
standard.
</P>
<P>
A price war that began a year ago brought down prices for
printers in the home market to a record low. Some printers, often
older models, are offered free with selected personal computer
purchases.
</P>
<P>
Some dealers said it is hard to make money as people are not
buying printers as often.
</P>
<P>
So to lure buyers back to the market, companies are upgrading
printer speed and color quality and adding more paper-handling
features. Top printer companies launch new products every six
months, according to market researchers.
</P>
<P>
But researchers also noted that the PC market demand for
ink-jet printers is growing steadily, while laser printers show
sluggishness. The world's sales of ink-jet printers last year grew
to 9.5 million units from 7.2 million units in 1995. Researchers
estimated that the sales for this will climb to 10.9 million.
</P>
<P>
But sales of laser printers will remain flat to 2.8 million
units this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
