<HEADLINE> First M-8 Group Summit Due in Istanbul in Mid-June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Eight Muslim countries (M-8) are to
hold their first summit meeting in the Turkish largest city,
Istanbul on June 15 to seek cooperation among them.
</P>
<P>
A statement by the Turkish Foreign Ministry said that before
the summit, foreign ministers of Turkey, Iran, Egypt, Indonesia,
Pakistan, Nigeria, Malaysia and Bangladesh will hold a council
meeting on June 14 and high-ranking officials from the M-8 Group
will convene a two-day commission meeting.
</P>
<P>
Turkish President Suleyman Demirel and Prime Minister
Necmettin Erbakan are expected to attend the summit, said the
statement.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan, enthusiastic initiator of the group, said earlier
that at the summit some important principles for the organization
will be stipulated in a bid to expand cooperation among the
member states.
</P>
<P>
During the summit, more than 50 cooperation projects among the
Muslim countries will be discussed, and the planned projects
cover various fields as trade, industry and telecommunications,
added the Turkish premier.
</P>
<P>
The M-8 Group, first proposed by Erbakan, was formed late last
year.
</P>
<P>
The Muslim bloc, which is aimed at boosting the multilateral
cooperation among the eight states, held its first foreign
ministers' meeting in Turkey in 1996 and decided to establish
its general secretariat in Istanbul.
</P>
<P>
The formation of the M-8 Group has provoked dissatisfaction
from the United States and European countries. They believe that
the group is directed against the Group-7 bloc that comprises the
U.S., Britain, France, Japan, Australia, Germany and Canada.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
