<DOCNO> XIE19970606.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tourists Not Have to Worry About Water in Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Holiday makers to this eastern
Mediterranean island don't have to worry about water during the
coming summer as local authorities are taking every possible
measure to ensure amply water supply to tourist areas.
</P>
<P>
Georgios Socratous, an official with the Water Development
Department, today promised that water supply to tourists in this
peak season will remain "uninterrupted and plentiful."
</P>
<P>
The sun-drenched island is actually suffering from water
shortage as water in the dams on the island takes up only 23
percent of their total capacity, falling by half from the level
last year.
</P>
<P>
To irrigate the island's booming tourism industry, local
authorities are exercising water supply cuts to the residents and
at the same time encourage water conservation.
</P>
<P>
Socratous told reporters today that his Department has reduced
water supply to cities across the island by 20 percent, for
agricultural purposes by 75 percent and for private gardening by
15 percent.
</P>
<P>
These have been coupled with an island-wide campaign to urge
citizens to "do their part in conserving the island's most
precious resource."
</P>
<P>
The government also gives incentives to homeowners to drill for
water on their property and connect newly-found supply to their
bathroom installations.
</P>
<P>
This, Socratous said, would provide up to 30 percent of each
household's total water consumption.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the island's first desalination plant which has been
operation since March will play an important role in serving the
southeastern tourist center of Ayia Napa as well as parts of the
southern coastal town of Larnaca.
</P>
<P>
A second desalination plant is expected to be completed in 1999
to serve the island's other tourist areas as well as the capital
Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
On their part, almost all hotels have installed water
reservation water tanks to guarantee their guests with 24-hour
supply of potable water.
</P>
<P>
Summer is the peak season for foreign tourists. Last year the
island attracted about 2 million visitors, bring about some 1.6
billion U.S. dollars in foreign currency earnings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
