<HEADLINE> Kissinger Says Necessary to Renew MFN to China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Henry Kissinger, former
secretary of state said on Thursday that revocation of the Most
Favored nation (MFN) trade status to China could only backfire and
do harm to the relations between the United States and China.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a Senate committee, Kissinger said he did not
believe that denial of MFN was the way for U.S. approach to china.
Rather, "we should give cooperative relations a chance," he said.
</P>
<P>
The secretary of state of the Nixon administration, who took
the initiative in early 1970s to thaw the relations between the
United States and China, said any challenge to the extension of
China's MFN status would do more damage to the United States "in
every corner of the war."
</P>
<P>
"Every Asian country will have to choose" between China and the
United States, "and they will blame us for having to be put in
that position," he added.
</P>
<P>
The MFN status is virtually the normal trade treatment which
the United States gives to most countries in the world.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton announced to renew the MFN status to
China on May 19. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
