<HEADLINE> Chimes Celebrating Hong Kong's Return to Motherland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Chimes from a museum in Hubei
province, central China, left here for Hong Kong today to perform
ceremonial services on July 1 for Hong Kong's return to motherland.
</P>
<P>
The chimes were made in 1984 as a replica of the "Zenghouyi
Chimes", historical relics about 2,400 years old, which were
unearthed in 1978 in Hubei's Suixian county.
</P>
<P>
Tan Dun, a Chinese-American musician will perform his work
"Symphony 1997" on these chimes. The work is 55 minutes long and
has three movements and a finale.
</P>
<P>
The musician said that chimes best embody the 5,000-year
history and culture of China.
</P>
<P>
For the Hong Kong performance, professional musicians have
formed the "China Chime Orchestra". On the night of July 1, the
orchestra is expected to perform one movement of the work in the
Hong Kong Exhibition Center. The work will be performed in its
entirety at an evening party on July 4.  
</P>
