<HEADLINE> 27 Countries, Regions Grant HKSAR Passport Holders Visa-Free Access </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 6 (Xinhua) -- A total of 27 countries and
regions in the world have so far agreed or announced to grant
holders of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR)
passport visa-free access, the chief of Hong Kong's Immigration
Department announced here today.
</P>
<P>
Director of Immigration Regina Ip Lau Suk-yee said 17 countries
and regions have announced their decisions on visa-free access for
SAR passport holders and her department has been informed by the
Chinese Foreign Ministry that 10 more countries and regions have
also decided to do so.
</P>
<P>
And three other countries -- the United States, Australia and
Japan -- have announced that SAR passport holders will be given
the same treatment as British Nationals Overseas or BN(O) passport
holders.
</P>
<P>
The immigration chief also said distribution of SAR passport
application forms will begin on June 10 this year and the forms
will be available at Hong Kong's immigration offices, district
offices and major post offices.
</P>
<P>
Some 5.5 million of Hong Kong's residents are eligible for SAR
passports, according to the director.
</P>
<P>
Application forms will also be obtainable in foreign countries
from all Chinese embassies and consulates-general within one week
or two, she said.
</P>
<P>
Under the Basic Law, Chinese citizens who hold Hong Kong
permanent identity cards will be eligible to apply for the HKSAR
passport. In short, persons of Chinese descent who hold, or are
qualified to hold, BN(O) passports or Hong Kong Certificates of
Identity (CIs), will be eligible as long as they remain Chinese
citizens.
</P>
<P>
If an applicant holds a valid BN(O) passport, he does not need
to give it up when the SAR passport is issued to him. He can
retain both passports and choose to travel on whichever passport
he likes, Ip said. However, if an applicant holds a valid Hong
Kong CI, he will have to surrender it for cancellation upon the
issue of the SAR passport.
</P>
<P>
No Hong Kong CIs will be issued or renewed after June 30, 1997,
because the CI holders will be eligible for SAR passports.
However, the CIs, which are valid beyond June 30, 1997, can
continue to be used until their normal expiry dates.
</P>
<P>
Of the more than 5 million Hong Kong residents, some 3 million
hold BN(O) passports and they can travel after July 1 this year
with their BN(O) passports first, Ip said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, most of the more 1.3 million Hong Kong CI holders
can travel with the CIs after July 1 this year as their CIs will
remain valid sometime after the handover.
</P>
<P>
As there is no deadline for the SAR passport application, it's
up to the Hong Kong residents themselves to decide when to apply
for the SAR passport, Ip continued.
</P>
<P>
SAR passport applications will be processed on a
"first-come-first-served" basis. But priority will be given to
applicants who have no travel documents or whose travel documents
will expire within 12 months, the immigration chief said.
</P>
<P>
Ip predicted that Hong Kong CI holders would be eager to apply
for SAR passports, which, she said, are more convenient as their
holders can enjoy visa-free access to at least 27 countries and
regions, against just two for the Hong Kong CI holders now.
</P>
<P>
The normal processing time for an SAR passport application is
15 working days. With a working staff of some 30, the Immigration
Department will be able to issue some 2,000 SAR passports daily
from July 3 on. The daily figure could be increased to 4,000 if
the department has more manpower in the future, according to the
Ip. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
