<HEADLINE> English Speech Contest For Hong Kong Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 6 (Xinhua) -- An English-language speech contest
for eleven students from eleven universities was held in Beijing
today to celebrate the return of Hong Kong to the motherland.
</P>
<P>
Fu Xiyong, a student from Shanghai's Fudan University, won
first place in the contest for students from Beijing, Shanghai,
Guangdong Province, and Hong Kong. Vice-Premier Li Lanqing, who
gave a speech in English at the opening of the contest, gave the
award to Fu.
</P>
<P>
Lam Tak Wing, a student at Beijing University of Languages and
Culture, and Wan Sai Man, of Qinghua University, won excellence
awards.
</P>
<P>
The contest was based on several English speech contests given
in Beijing, Shanghai, and Guangdong starting in April. Zhang
Xiaowen, vice-minister in charge of the State Education Commission
(SEC), the contest's sponsor, said that the contest was designed
to help young students express their patriotism and greetings
for Hong Kong's return.
</P>
<P>
Hu Wenzhong, chairman of the judges panel, said that the
contest was "a high-level English speech contest" and that "we
could not help being moved by many of them."
</P>
<P>
Hu, a well-known English language professor, encouraged
all contestants by saying that, although they were all speaking on
the same topic, they succeeded in impressing the audience with
different stories in different ways.
</P>
<P>
He pointed to a "welcome change" where non-English majors
competed with English majors on the same stage.
</P>
<P>
Among the audience were officials for the SEC, the Hong Kong
and Macao Affairs Office of the State Council, the Ministry of
Foreign Affairs, and students from Beijing-based
universities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
