<HEADLINE> Canada's Jobless Rate Down Slightly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Canada's unemployment rate edged
down 0.1 percentage points in May to 9.5 percent despite strong
job gains.
</P>
<P>
Statistics Canada reported today that employment in May rose by
an estimated 61,000, the third consecutive monthly increase,
bringing gains since February to 156,000.
</P>
<P>
In May, the labor force expanded by 51,000, which partly offset
the strong job gains.
</P>
<P>
Employment continued to rise in the private sector. In May, an
estimated 52,000 more people were working in the private sector.
</P>
<P>
Little change has been recorded in the public sector for almost
a year, the federal agency said.
</P>
<P>
In May, employment in community, business and personal services
rose by 76,000, bringing gains since September 1996 to 232,000.
</P>
<P>
Employment in the goods sector changed little. In construction,
employment declined by 14,000.
</P>
<P>
In other primary industries, employment was up 8,000, partially
offsetting losses of 12,000 jobs over the previous three months.
Employment in manufacturing held steady for the second consecutive
month following a strong gain in March.
</P>
<P>
"Two-thirds of the increase in May was in Ontario (province)
where employment rose by 41,000, bringing the gains in the past
three months to 101,000," the agency said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
