<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Unemployment Falls in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The number of unemployed people in
Germany fell by 91,200 to 4.23 million in May over April, a rate
of 11.1 percent, but was still 430,000 higher than a year earlier,
the Federal Labour Office said today.
</P>
<P>
The office said joblessness remained at a post-war record high,
and stripping out seasonal factors, dole queues lengthened by
56,000 to almost 4.36 million.
</P>
<P>
Office chief Bernhard Jagoda stressed that the German economy
was still not strong enough to reverse the unfavorable trends on
the job market.
</P>
<P>
Jagoda also warned that Germany's average unemployment this
year would reach 4.2 million, exceeding the 3.95 million projected
by the federal government.
</P>
<P>
High unemployment is pushing up Germany's social security
spending, making it more difficult for Bonn to cut the budget
deficit below three percent of gross domestic product (GDP), as
required by the Maastricht Treaty for European Union countries
wanting to join the single currency, the Euro. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
