<HEADLINE> Kuerten Beats Dewulf to Reach French Open Final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Unseeded Gustavo Kuerten of Brazil
beat Belgian qualifier Filip Dewulf in four sets here on Friday to
reach the final of the French Open tennis tournament.
</P>
<P>
The 20-year-old Brazilian downed Dewulf 6-1, 3-6, 6-1, 7-6
(7-4) in two hours and 14 minutes, becoming the first Brazilian
man to make the Grand Slam final.
</P>
<P>
Kuerten broke Dewulf twice and won the first set in 25 minutes,
before the Belgian gained a 5-3 lead en route to winning the
second set after an early swap of breaks.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilian, who ranked 66th in the world, retained his best
in the third while Dewulf committed numerous unforced errors.
</P>
<P>
The fourth set saw both players committing their styles with
unforced errors from either side before the scoreboard was
deadlocked 5-5 and 6-6.
</P>
<P>
In the tiebreaker, Dewulf who ranked 122, went up 4-3, but hit
two forehands low into the net before Kuerten taking the last two
points to seal the first semifinal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
