<HEADLINE> French Forget Retires from Tennis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 6 (Xinhua) -- France's Guy Forget said on Friday he
was retiring from tennis after 15 years on the circuit.
</P>
<P>
"It was not an easy decision to make. I still felt at times I
could recover," said the 32-year-old who turned professional in
1982.
</P>
<P>
Forget reached his career-high fourth ranking in the world in
1991, and advanced to the quarter-finals at Wimbledon three times.
</P>
<P>
The Frenchman said he would play his last singles tournament in
France in October.
</P>
<P>
Born in Morocco, Forget secured the decisive rubber in France's
Davis Cup victory over the United States in 1991.
</P>
<P>
The same year, he won six ATP titles, including the Paris Open
with a win over Pete Sampras in the final.
</P>
<P>
Forget was also one of the best doubles players on the circuit,
winning 28 titles, most of them with Swiss Jakob Hlasek. 
</P>
</TEXT>
