<HEADLINE> New Car Sales Grow Modestly in UK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 6 (Xinhua) -- New car registrations in Britain
rose by 2.5 percent to 169,886 in May over the same month last
year, figures released by the Society of Motor Manufacturers and
Traders (SMMT) show.
</P>
<P>
The figures showed new car sales in the first five months of
this year went up by 4.9 percent to 902,167 over the same period
last year.
</P>
<P>
The data confirms that Britain is one of the most buoyant new
car markets in Europe but also a tough one, the society says.
</P>
<P>
SMMT said that imports made up 63.5 percent of May's
registrations compared with 61.5 percent a year ago. In the year
to date, imports have taken a 64.7 percent market share, compared
with 61.5 percent for the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
"A small reduction in fleet registrations was offset by a
modest improvement in the private retail sector. Overall,
registrations are holding up well with a year to date rise of 4.9
percent," said Roger King, SMMT Director of Public Affairs.
</P>
<P>
"Nevertheless, the modest growth in May shows the market
remains a tough one," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
