<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Algerian President's Party Wins Parliamentary Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Algeria's National Democratic Rally
(RND), founded four months ago and seen as a major supporter of
President Liamine Zeroual, won 155 seats in the country's
parliamentary election on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Together with the former ruling National Liberation Front
(FLN), which won 64 seats, the two parties formed the largest
force in the new 380-seat National People's Assembly, Algerian
Interior Minister Mostefa Benmansour said today.
</P>
<P>
Two Islam-leaning parties, the Movement of Society for Peace
and the Ennahda, won 69 and 34 seats respectively, forming the
second largest parliamentary force.
</P>
<P>
The Socialist Forces Front and the Rally for Culture and
Democracy both got 19 seats, while the leftist Workers Party won
only four seats.
</P>
<P>
Three smaller parties won five seats each, and independent
movements won 11 seats.
</P>
<P>
The new parliament is Algeria's first elected multi-party
assembly since independence in 1962. Algeria was run as a
one-party state by the FLN for nearly three decades until the
first attempt at a parliamentary vote in December 1991.
</P>
<P>
The election, which radical Islamists were poised to win, was
cancelled by the military-backed authorities in January 1992 and
shortly afterwards the country plunged into violence. An estimated
60,000 people have died in the troubles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
