<HEADLINE> Chinese Leader Visits German Daimler-Benz Aerospace AG </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MUNICH, Germany, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Chinese leader Li Ruihuan
today visited Germany's Daimler-Benz Aerospace AG (Dasa), the
aircraft and aerospace subsidiary of the Daimler-Benz group.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with board members of the Daimler-Benz group
and Dasa at Dasa's headquarters, Li, chairman of the Chinese
People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC), said that
China and the Daimler-Benz group have enjoyed a long history of
cooperation which has continued to expand in recent years.
</P>
<P>
He expressed satisfaction with cooperation between China and
Dasa in aviation, adding that he hopes the company will do better
in improving quality, security and services, which he said will
help build a more solid foundation for long-term cooperation
between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Dietrich Russel, head of Dasa's Civil Aircraft and Helicopters
Unit, and Peter Fietzek, who is responsible for the Eastern
Hemisphere at Daimler-Benz AG, briefed the Chinese leader on Dasa
and its activities in China.
</P>
<P>
They stressed that China is an immensely important growth
market for all the business units of the Daimler-Benz group.
</P>
<P>
They said that Dasa has established 12 joint ventures in China
with the focus on aviation, satellite communications and solar
energy utilization.
</P>
<P>
Those ventures have grown smoothly and have achieved remarkable
results, they said, adding that they hope the mutually beneficial
cooperation will be further strengthened.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, the Chinese leader also viewed some products
of Dasa, and watched the performance of an EC135 helicopter.
</P>
<P>
As a partner of the European Airbus Consortium, Dasa is
involved in the construction of all Airbus aircraft purchased by
China.
</P>
<P>
In May, China ordered 35 new Airbus aircraft of the A320
family, raising the total number of the aircraft ordered by China
to 60.
</P>
<P>
As an Airbus partner, Dasa is also involved in an
Asian-European project to build a 100-seater passenger aircraft. A
framework agreement on the project was reached in May.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the company is also cooperating with China, Singapore
and France in building a light helicopter, EC120.
</P>
<P>
It has established a joint venture with China to develop, build
and market civil satellites for communication and earth
observation purposes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
