<HEADLINE> Iran Terms Deadline Set by Taliban as "Illegal" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 6 (Xinhua) -- A senior Iranian official today
termed the deadline set by the Taliban for Iranian diplomats to
leave Kabul, the capital of Afghanistan, as "totally illegal and
not in accord with any international law."
</P>
<P>
Iranian Judicial Chief Mohammad Yazadi made the statement
while addressing multitudes of worshipers gathered at the
Mausoleum of late spiritual leader Khomeini in southern Tehran,
the capital of Iran, the official news agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
However, IRNA gave no details about the deadline.
</P>
<P>
Yazadi said that Afghanistan's situation was not yet clear and
Iranian officials hope to witness unification of the Jihadi
groups and resolution of their problems through negotiations.
</P>
<P>
IRNA also reported that Iranian Deputy Foreign Minister
Allaeddin Boroujerdi arrived in Afghanistan's Mazar-i-Sharif
today at the invitation of the United Islamic Front of
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Boroujerdi said that recent developments in Afghanistan proved
futility of military solution for settlement of the Afghan
crisis, stressing the necessity of solving the intricacies of the
situation through negotiations and mutual understanding.
</P>
<P>
He added that Afghan nation was made up of different tribes,
whose contribution to the political sovereignty of their country
was the only way out of the traditional dispute.
</P>
<P>
He expressed hope that all Afghan tribes should strive for
restoration of peace and calm in their homeland in a sound
atmosphere and for reaching mutual understanding through
formation of an Islamic government. He also hoped that
Afghanistan's neighbors play positive roles in that direction.
</P>
</TEXT>
