<DOCNO> XIE19970606.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Simplify Telecoms Terminal Equipment Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission, the
European Union (EU)'s executive body, is aiming to simplify the
marketing of telecommunications terminal equipment in all its
member states, it was learned here today.
</P>
<P>
Following a proposal from Martin Bangemann, EU commissioner for
telecommunication policies, the EC today adopted a directive aimed
at stipulating a new framework to support the market for
telecommunications terminals.
</P>
<P>
The proposal meets the changing needs of the telecommunications
market caused by the explosive growth of mobile services and the
prospect of full liberalization of the supply of
telecommunications networks and services from January 1998.
</P>
<P>
When implemented, the new framework will speed up the time
taken to bring new equipment onto the market and will extend the
single European market to all types of radio and wire-based
telecommunications terminals.
</P>
<P>
The proposed framework is a fast and flexible one which relies
on self-certification by industry, rather than cumbersome testing
by outside bodies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970606.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Importation of Sugar Needed in Philippines: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines needs to import some
300,000 to 350,000 tons of sugar during the next crop season to
fill in a projected supply shortfall, a senior sugar official said
today.
</P>
<P>
Sugar Regulatory Administrator Wilson Gamboa said a plan for
sugar importation will be taken up by the Sugar Regulatory
Administration Board later this month and then submitted to
President Fidel Ramos for approval.
</P>
<P>
The planned sugar imports for the 1997-98 crop year are vital
in the buildup of security reserve which shall not go down below a
two-month supply of sugar, Gamboa said.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines keeps a strategic sugar reserve of 350,000 to
400,000 tons in order to meet the increasing local consumption of
sugar, according to Gamboa.
</P>
<P>
Placing the annual growth rate of the country's sugar
consumption at 4.5 percent, Gamboa predicted the local sugar
consumption shall reach 2.1 million tons in the next sugar crop
year.
</P>
<P>
But the production level, on the other hand, is seen to reach
some 1.8 million tons, thus resulting in a shortfall of around
300,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines will start importing sugar in September 1997 or
in March 1998, according to Gamboa.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
