<DOCNO> XIE19970606.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, Portugal Prepare to Build Macao-Zhuhai Bridge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, June 6 (Xinhua) -- An informal working panel was
established here today to make detailed preparations for the
construction of a bridge linking Macao and neighboring Zhuhai in
south China's Guangdong province, officials announced.
</P>
<P>
Xie Houhe, head of the Chinese side of the Sino-Portuguese
Infrastructure Coordination Commission, which was established in
Beijing on April 30, made the announcement together with his
Portuguese counterpart Leonel Miranda after a closed-door meeting
this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The panel will start working soon to make geological survey and
other investigations so that a feasibility study report could be
submitted to the second plenary session of the commission, Xie
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Chinese and Portuguese officials on the commission concluded
today a four-day survey on the possible site of the bridge in
Zhuhai and Macao. They have decided on the general location of the
 bridge.
</P>
<P>
The proposed bridge will run from a major Zhuhai island called
Hengqin and to a piece of reclamation land between Macao's two
islands -- Taipa and Coloane. It is designed to be 760 meters
long, 13 meters above water and have six lanes.
</P>
<P>
According to a report in a local newspaper, the bridge will
cost 95 million Hong Kong dollars (about 12.29 million U.S.
dollars). The cost will in principle be shared equally by
Zhuhai and Macao.
</P>
<P>
"It is the wish of many Macao residents and the wish of our
commission to complete the bridge before 1999," said Xie, who is
also chief of the Macao Division in the Hong Kong and Macao
Affairs Office of the State Council.
</P>
<P>
"We will work hard to make that dream come true," he said.
</P>
<P>
The proposed bridge, which will become the second land link
between Macao and Zhuhai, is the first major project the
commission has undertaken. Other projects will follow, officials
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
