<HEADLINE> Information Technology Exhibition Sees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
Fast-Growing Computer Market in Kenya
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of enthusiastic Kenyans
swarmed into the sixth Africa Information Technology Exhibitions
and Conferences (AITEC) which is to end here later today, a symbol of
the fast-expanding computer market in Kenya and the continent.
</P>
<P>
The three-day AITEC, the largest since it started in Harare
in 1987, attracted 67 exhibitors this year with the most advanced
software, hardware, telecommunication systems and office
equipment displayed and more than 2,000 visitors coming in a day.
</P>
<P>
The AITEC was attended by 30 exhibitors with more than
7,000 visitors.
</P>
<P>
"It has been a resounding success... The outstanding feature
of the show, besides tremendous exposure of the internet, is the
atmosphere of friendship and cooperation between exhibitors and
visitors," said Sean Moroney, head organizer of AITEC.
</P>
<P>
"All exhibitors have been very pleased with quality of
visitors and many have reported positive sales results already,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Kenya-based Africa Online, a premier internet
service provider in Africa with offices in Ghana, Cote D'Ivoire,
Tanzania, Uganda and Zimbabwe, their visitors are curious about
the new technological advancement and most of them are keen on
doing serious business.
</P>
<P>
"We have sold over 10 subscriptions already," said a
representative of the firm.
</P>
<P>
"There is a big potential of the computer market in both
Kenya and Africa," a manager from the Comtech System Limited
company, one of all the seven local dealers here for world-famous
Compaq, told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
"We are very optimism. The market here is very strong and
expands very fast," he said. His company sold 500 computer sets
in Kenya last year.
</P>
<P>
Computech, another local dealer of Compaq, sold some 1,000
computer sets in 1996. Compaq now holds more than 20 percent
share of the Kenyan computer market.
</P>
<P>
Now there are more than 300 information technology companies
in Kenya which holds 60 percent of the computer market in the
eastern African region partly as a result of the economic
liberalization in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Duties on imported computer-related products stand at
five percent, the lowest in east Africa, said an IBM officer at
the show.
</P>
<P>
Currently there are estimatedly 240,000 computer sets
operating in Kenya. The Internet users reached 5, 000 in Nairobi
with a total of 11 internet service providers.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government has introduced a number of specialized
courses such as computer science, information technology and
management information services in national polytechincs and
other technical training institutions in the country.
</P>
<P>
The computer companies participating at the show also include
Carl Bro, Gath Management, Abacus, Modern Business
Communications, Microsoft, Copycat, DEC and other giants in the
field. 
</P>
</TEXT>
