<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Civil Service Exam Becoming Popular in China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The idea of getting a government
job was just a distant dream for many Chinese, as recently as
three years ago, no matter how ambitious or competent they might
be, if they lacked the proper academic background, but things have
changed.
</P>
<P>
Now there is a simple and effective way for them to realize
their dreams, with an open exam system to choose civil servants
now being used in most of the country.
</P>
<P>
China decided to change its civil service system for both
central and local governments in 1993 and the following year the
Personnel Ministry formulated the "Provisional Regulation on the
Hiring of Civil Servants", which state that any government
employees who are not in leading positions must take part in the
open examination.
</P>
<P>
"The practice of choosing civil servants by an exam has helped
create a cleaner image of the government among the people and has
improved the general quality of civil servants," said Xu Songtao,
vice-minister of personnel.
</P>
<P>
Starting in 1994, the Personnel Ministry and the Organization
Department of the Chinese Communist Party Central Committee held
joint exams three times to recruit 1,722 civil servants and other
workers for central government departments.
</P>
<P>
During the same period, 28 provinces, autonomous regions and
municipalities have recruited nearly 19,000 civil servants for
various provincial departments through the same process.
</P>
<P>
The three open exams attracted more than 48,000 applicants,
while over 210,000 people across the country joined the contest at
the provincial level.
</P>
<P>
"The exam system has received a warm welcome from the general
public because it reflects the principle of openness, fairness,
competition and choosing the best," Xu noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970606.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Civil Service Exam Becoming Popular in China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The new system is popular, he added, because many units
have recruited civil servants regardless of where they are from or
what their social status is, based completely on their competence.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, the Railways Ministry and the National Bureau of
Oceanography took the lead in recruiting civil servants from all
over China, instead of from the capital city alone.
</P>
<P>
The Communications Ministry, the State Education Commission,
and other central government departments followed suit, so
did provinces and municipalities like Hainan, Hebei and Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, a number of provinces and cities, like Fujian,
Gansu, Jilin and Xi'an, have even allowed local farmers to compete
for government posts.
</P>
<P>
Wang Limin, a young farmer from Yongji County in Jilin
Province, became a worker at the County Procuratorate in 1995
after successfully taking a provincial exam for civil servants at
the county level.
</P>
<P>
"The new system has provided everyone, including farmers like
us, with a chance to engage in fair competition," he exclaimed.
</P>
<P>
The Personnel Ministry's next goal is to set up a complete exam
system for central authorities and for governments at the
township, county, prefectural and provincial levels, the
vice-minister said.
</P>
<P>
"We will strive to introduce a complete, standardized, and
modern system for selecting civil servants in China by exams by
the end of this century," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
