<HEADLINE> 25 Rebels Killed, 60 Injured in North Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 6 (Xinhua) -- About 25 Tamil rebels were killed
and 60 others injured today by government troops who recaptured
Pariyamadu Town in northern Sri Lanka, according to a military
spokesman here this evening.
</P>
<P>
Rp Witana, the spokesman, said the troops who launched
Operation "Jaya Sikuru" (Certain Victory) on May 13, have overcome
resistance put up by the rebels and recaptured the town south of
Puliyankulam this morning.
</P>
<P>
The Sri Lankan Air Force engaged targets in depth and provided
close air support and artillery was also used, inflicting heavy
casualties on rebel reinforcements.
</P>
<P>
The rebels were forced to withdraw further northward in
Puliyankulam and southeastward in the Oddusudan area.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said ground troops estimated that at least 25
rebels had been killed and more than 60 others wounded while the
government forces had one officer and eight soldiers killed and
one officer and 11 soldiers injured in action.
</P>
<P>
The government troops at present are in the process of
consolidating in the newly recaptured areas.
</P>
<P>
The rebels of the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam have been
fighting a guerrilla war against the Sri Lankan government since
1983 for a separate state in the northeast of the country.
</P>
