<DOCNO> XIE19970606.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Worst Fire-Damaged Forest Area Restored </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, Jane 6 (Xinhua) -- In a decade since China's worst
forest fire raged through Greater Hinggan Mountains Forest in
Heilongjiang Province in the northeast, thousands of hectares of
new trees have been planted to help ease the painful memories left
by the blaze.
</P>
<P>
According to a source from the Ministry of Forestry, 92.4
percent of the total one million hectares of fire-damaged area in
the Greater Hinggan Mountains have been re-forested, which has
significantly controlled the balance of ecological environment
there.
</P>
<P>
"Now most of the area is now dotted with pine trees and natural
second growth trees, with a background of burnt tree stumps as a
grim reminder of what happened," a source from the Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Forestry Xu Youfang said that there is no precedent
in the world for the restoration of forest resources on a such
large scale in such a cold and high-latitude area like that of
the Greater Hinggan Mountains.
</P>
<P>
Soon after the 1987 fire, the relevant departments of both the
central and local governments launched a forest restoration
project, he said. To date, a total of 710 million yuan (85.5
million US dollars) has been invested to the project through
various channels.
</P>
<P>
Over the past ten years, the yearly average forest area planted
in the Greater Hinggan Mountain was more than 20,000 hectares, 75
times more than before the fire.
</P>
<P>
Around 1,000 researchers and technicians from eight research
institutes and universities across China have participated in the
forest restoration project.
</P>
<P>
The Greater Hinggan Mountain region is one of the country's
richest bases for primeval timber and forestry products. It also
plays an vital role in maintaining the ecological environment and
promoting sustained economic development in northeast China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
