<HEADLINE> Fire at Yangtze River Tanker Extinguished, Nine Still Missing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 6 (Xinhua) -- A fire on a tanker anchored in the
Nanjing section of the Yangtze River, east China's Jiangsu
Province, was extinguished this morning, but nine people are still
missing, the Ministry of Communications announced today.
</P>
<P>
Reports confirm that a total of 48 people were on board the
"Daqing 243" oil tanker, which had stopped at the Qixia dock,
including 47 crew members and a non-crew member. Thirty-nine of
them have been rescued.
</P>
<P>
The fire broke out on 2:44 p.m on June 4, and was controlled
by that night.
</P>
<P>
The ministry says that the accident site has been cordoned off,
and will not cause heavy crude oil pollution.
</P>
<P>
An investigation group jointly set up by the Ministry of
Communications, other state departments concerned, and departments
concerned of Jiangsu Province is investigating the cause of the
accident. 
