<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Car Industry Welcomes Tariff Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Australia's automotive industry
today welcomed a government decision to freeze tariffs for five
years after 2000 by promising job stability and major future
investment.
</P>
<P>
Leading car and component manufacturers unanimously expressed
their welcome to the government decision to keep tariffs at 15
percent until the year 2005.
</P>
<P>
Australia's car tariffs, currently standing at 22.5 percent,
will fall by 2.5 percent a year until they reach 15 percent in
2000.
</P>
<P>
The decision was announced by Prime Minister John Howard
Thursday night following several days of intense negotiations with
state premiers and chief executives of the four car makers --
Ford, General-Motors Holden, Toyota and Mitsubishi.
</P>
<P>
The government's Industry Commission recommended last month
that car tariffs be phased down from 15 percent to 5 percent
between 2000 and 2004.
</P>
<P>
Ford Australia said the decision has ensured that Australia
remains a competitive location for auto investment.
</P>
<P>
Ford Australia President David Morgan was quoted by the
Australian Associated Press as saying the decision has also
secured jobs for 7,000 Ford employees and given the company the
potential to invest in further export programs. More than 45,000
people are employed in the industry.
</P>
<P>
Mitsubishi Motors Australia Ltd. said it is now confident of
securing a 450 million Australian dollar investment in its
Adelaide manufacturing plant following the tariff decision.
</P>
<P>
"Our next investment needs to be decided by the end of 1998 and
it will be a number somewhere between 400 million Australian
dollars and 450 million Australian dollars," Managing Director
Mike Quinn said.
</P>
<P>
Toyota and Mitsubishi last month urged the Australian
government not to endorse a radical car tariff reduction proposal
by the official Industry Commission, or they would reconsider
their investment plans in Australia.
</P>
<P>
Holden Managing Director Jim Wiemels said the tariff decision
has given Holden the confidence it needs to increase its
investments in the country.
</P>
<P>
Wiemels said the outcome has also laid the foundation for
Holden and other car manufacturers to become major manufacturers
within the Asia Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
The Federation of Automotive Products Manufacturers, which
represents more than 200 component manufacturers, said the tariff
decision would help boost component exports.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
