<DOCNO> XIE19970606.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand, South Asian Nations Form Economic Grouping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Thailand and three South Asian
countries -- Bangladesh, India and Sri Lanka -- today declared the
establishment of an economic cooperation grouping.
</P>
<P>
The announcement resulted from a three-day ministerial meeting
of the four countries in Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
The grouping, called the Bangladesh-India-Sri Lanka-Thailand
Economic Cooperation (BIST-EC), is aimed at promoting economic
development and exchanges between the two sub-regions -- South and
Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the vice ministerial rank of the four
countries today signed a declaration on the creation of BIST-EC.
</P>
<P>
BIST-EC will be an important bridge linking the two regional
groupings -- ASEAN (Association of Southeast Asian Nations) and
SAARC (South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation), of which
India, Bangladesh and Sri Lanka are members.
</P>
<P>
The grouping is aimed at creating an environment for rapid
economic development through identification and implementation of
specific cooperation projects in the sectors of trade, investment,
industry, technology, human resource development, tourism,
agriculture, energy, infrastructure and transportation.
</P>
<P>
Thailand has eagerly pushed BIST-EC's establishment at a time
when its exports are facing a slowdown and the new grouping will
help Thailand expand its markets in its neighboring nations to its
west.
</P>
<P>
Annual ministerial meetings will be held on the basis of
alphabetical rotation.
</P>
<P>
A representative of Myanmar was present at the signing
ceremony as an observer. It is believed that Myanmar will the next
to gain a BIST-EC membership after it has become a full member of
ASEAN in July this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
