<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Prime Minister Ends China Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi
ended his two-day official visit to China here today, saying that
that his trip was fruitful and constructive.
</P>
<P>
Before flying home this afternoon, he told a press conference
that his visit is part of a series of high-level contacts between
Italy and China.
</P>
<P>
Italian President Oscar Luigi Scalfaro will visit China later
this year, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that Italy pays close attention to expanding relations
between the two countries and those between the European Union
(EU) and China.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized the intention of increasing trade handled by
Italian small and medium-sized enterprises with China and boosting
investment made by them in China. He noted that such enterprises
constitute the mainstay and advantage of the Italian industry, and
can best meet China's needs for diversity in its industrialization
drive, he said.
</P>
<P>
He vowed that the Italian government will help smaller Italian
enterprises lay a solid foundation for their long-term investment
in China.
</P>
<P>
In response to a question, he said that China enjoys the full
support of Italy in its bid to join the World Trade Organization
(WTO). He said that Italy is trying to help solve remaining
problems in this regard promptly.
</P>
<P>
Augusto Fantozzi, Italian Minister of Foreign Trade, said at
the press conference that in a recent meeting with WTO
Director-General Renato Ruggiero in Paris, he was told that China's
WTO entry is "very well-oriented to the positive result possibly
within the year." 
</P>
</TEXT>
