<HEADLINE> HK Gold Imports Hit Seven-year High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's gold imports reached
their highest level in seven years for the first quarter of 1997,
rising threefold over the same period last year, today's Hong Kong
Standard reported.
</P>
<P>
The World Gold Council manager for Hong Kong and southern
China, Emily Li, said 120 tons of gold bars were imported in the
first quarter.
</P>
<P>
And sales during the period jumped by 20 percent over the same
1996 quarter to 13.5 tons, she said, adding high consumption
resulted from a mix of low prices and keen demand, especially
during the Lunar New Year.
</P>
<P>
Li expected retail sales to continue to increase this year
because many gold products had been shaped for the handover.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong remains Asia's No. 1 gold distribution center in terms
of quantity and jewelry designs.
</P>
<P>
It imported and distributed 2,900 tons of gold bars in the past
ten years, Li said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970606.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao Unemployment Rate Hits 3.5 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Macao's unemployment rate between
February and April this year hit 3.5 percent, up slightly from the
previous period, latest statistics show.
</P>
<P>
Figures released by the Macao Census and Statistics Department
show that the jobless rate was 0.9 percent down from the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
However, it rose slightly from the January-March period, when
the rate was recorded at 3.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The sub-employment rate reached 0.9 percent between February
and April, compared with 1.7 percent from the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
Macao has witnessed an economic slowdown for the past two
years, with the unemployment rate hitting the highest of 4.8
percent last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
