<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia, Thailand to Strengthen Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia and Thailand today
agreed to set up more joint committees to deal with matters
relating to their relations and further enhance their existing
close cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also agreed to fix a time frame for the
implementation of joint projects to ensure that such projects are
completed on schedule.
</P>
<P>
The agreements were reached at a meeting here today attended by
Thai Deputy Prime Minister Amnuay Virawan and Malaysian Acting
Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim, both of whom are also finance
ministers.
</P>
<P>
Briefing reporters after the meeting, the Malaysian Finance
Ministry's Deputy Secretary-General Aris Othman said the meeting
also discussed ways to standardize the customs procedures of both
countries in an effort to further increase bilateral trade with
the removal of as many obstacles as possible.
</P>
<P>
Aris said that during the discussion on a proposed land bridge
between Pulau Pinang and Songkla, it was suggested that a land
bridge be constructed to link Pulau Pinang with Pattani instead
because of the deeper sea level between the two points.
</P>
<P>
The construction of gas and petroleum pipelines was also
proposed along with the land bridge, he said.
</P>
<P>
The official said the two countries also agreed to discuss
further the Goods in Transit Agreement and the Trade Integrated
Service Agreement before discussions on the matter during the
ASEAN summit in December this year.
</P>
<P>
The Thai deputy prime minister is leading a 10-member
delegation on a three-day official visit to Malaysia beginning
Thursday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
