<DOCNO> XIE19970606.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Steps up Fight Against Drug, Money </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 6 (Xinhua) -- South Africa has been
contacting with regional and international law enforcement agencies
in the fight against drug trafficking and money laundering.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here today, Justice Minister Dullah Omar
said South African has signed several international conventions
aimed at establishing a cooperative framework to exchange
information with other countries on drug smuggling.
</P>
<P>
He said South Africa's recent amended extradition act would
tighten the net around drug traffickers who he said could now
stand trial overseas.
</P>
<P>
A key issue under review is streamlining the judicial systems
of member countries of the Southern African Development Community.
</P>
<P>
A pact to this effect, signed by SADC heads of state in
Maseru last year, outlawed all forms of drug trafficking, he
added.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, a further step was taken when
southern and eastern African states agreed to establish a
regional task force to fight money laundering.
</P>
<P>
South Africa is also entitled to international assistance
following the signing of a mutual assistance regulation with the
United Nations, the United Kingdom, the United States and
Northern Ireland, he said.
</P>
<P>
Similar arrangements are also under negotiation with
Argentina, Brazil, Chile and Paraguay.
</P>
<P>
Police statistics indicated that only 10 to 15 percent of all
drugs smuggled into South Africa have been seized, which in the
first six months of last year amounted to 300,000 Mandrax
tablets, 77 km of cocaine and 783 km of heroin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
