<DOCNO> XIE19970606.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: United Opposition in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 6 (Xinhua) -- One day hopes for a united
opposition were painted stronger than ever in the Philippines, and
the other day one possible partner threw them into clouds.
</P>
<P>
Senator Miriam Defensor Santiago, president of the People's
Reform Party (PRP), announced Thursday that she had broken off
talks with three other opposition parties which wanted to unify
all oppositions to give the ruling party a good fight in the 1998
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
"I was led into the talks under false promises," she said,
adding that she was told earlier that all opposition parties would
be given "equal chances of fielding a common presidential
candidate".
</P>
<P>
"But this is no longer the case," she said in response to a
declaration attributed to Senate President Ernesto Maceda that the
proposed merged parties would choose their presidential candidate
only between Vice President Joseph Estrada and Senator Edgardo
Angara.
</P>
<P>
Estrada heads the Partido ng Masang Pilipino (PMP) while Angara
is chairman of the Laban ng Demokratikong Pilipino (Laban).
Besides PMP, Laban and PRP, the united opposition would also
include Nationalist People's Coalition (NPC) headed by Maceda.
</P>
<P>
The latest development in the opposition bloc will certainly be
a good message to the ruling Lakas-NUCD party, which has scoffed
at the future of the proposed united opposition.
</P>
<P>
"I think what they have achieved is to build a jeep with four
or five steering wheels," said Gabriel Claudio, deputy secretary
general of the Lakas-NUCD. "When they are able to come up with a
formula on how to choose their common standard-bearer, which I
think is the real bottom line, I don't think then that this will
work."
</P>
<P>
Claudio's views are shared by some politicians in the country.
Since not a single opposition party can compete with the
formidable ruling party, it is a good idea to bring all opposition
parties under a single political umbrella, but the real test is
who will be the standard bearer.
</P>
<P>
Vice President Estrada, a former movie star popular among the
poor people, has been leading all opinion polls in approval
rating. He has already expressed his aspiration for the presidency
and has not lost an election since he entered politics to run for
town mayor in 1972. He has cut all ties with the Fidel Ramos
administration by resigning as the head of the Presidential
Anti-Crime Commission Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Santiago, less popular than Estrada in surveys, is a feisty
former judge who vows to jail all corrupt officials if she becomes
president. She narrowly lost to Ramos in the 1992 presidential
race, accused him of poll fraud and challenged him to a boxing
match which Ramos did not take up. She said earlier that she would
join the united opposition if she could become the common
candidate.
</P>
<P>
Angara, president of the biggest opposition Laban, is not as
popular as Estrada, but he has a great party machine that Estrada
and Santiago don't have. While Estrada and Santiago both have the
backing of small parties, Laban currently has 26 congressmen, 13
senators, 7 provincial governors and over 300 local mayors.
</P>
<P>
Then comes the question of selecting the standard bearer.
Estrada has said he does not want to be a vice president any more;
Angara is talking like the leader of the opposition parties;
Santiago is quitting talks and expressing dissatisfaction over
Estrada.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts said the united opposition may come into
existence only when all parties concerned can come up with a set
of rules for the game and no party will back out if its leader has
not been chosen.
</P>
<P>
But on the contrary, it seems none of the three aspirants is
ready to make a concession. Therefore, some local analysts said
the united opposition would not prosper, describing it as a "time
bomb" that can explode at any time.
</P>
<P>
After Santiago announced her withdrawal, Maceda quickly
clarified his statement, saying that he made it at a time when he
was not yet informed by Angara that Santiago had already decided
to join the new party.
</P>
<P>
The Laban party was also "shocked". Laban treasurer Ernesto
Herrera said what the other three parties can do is to court
Santiago again.
</P>
<P>
But local analysts are asking whether it is too late to bring
her back. Or even if she comes back, will voters see a real united
opposition at this time next year in the presidential election,
they query. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
