<DOCNO> XIE19970606.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kindergartens in Sarawak Close Due to Outbreak of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Kindergartens registered with
the state government have been closed until further notice in
Sarawak, East Malaysia, due to the outbreak of the deadly
Coxsackie B virus, according to the Malaysian national news agency
Bernama today.
</P>
<P>
The Coxsackie B virus, known to infect children below four
years of age, has so far claimed 17 lives in Sarawak since April
14 when the first fatal case in the state was reported.
</P>
<P>
Bernama quoted state education department director Putit Matzen
as saying in Kuching, Sarawak's capital, today the decision was
aimed at preventing young children from crowding around and from
being exposed to the viral infection.
</P>
<P>
Putit said schools in the affected areas need not close, but
parents could choose not to send pupils of grade one to three to
class if they feared the pupils would be infected.
</P>
<P>
The official said that the department was leaving it to
headmasters to decide whether there was a need to close primary
one to three classes in their respective schools.
</P>
<P>
Putit called on pre-schools in the state that had not
registered with the state education department to take similar
action.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Health Ministry Thursday advised operators of
places of interest in Sarawak frequented by preschoolers to
temporarily stop operations.
</P>
<P>
Health Minister Chua Jui Meng said here today the government
staff in Sarawak are working very hard at preventing and
controlling this problem by consistently being in consultation
with experts from the World Health Organization.
</P>
<P>
However, Chua said there was no need for the public to be
unduly alarmed as everything was under control.
</P>
<P>
The Coxsackie virus was named after Coxsackie town, New York,
the United States, where the virus was first discovered in 1948.
The virus has A and B types with B type dangerous, causing fever
and sore throat, and also harm to brain, nerve and heart.
</P>
</TEXT>
