<HEADLINE> French Language Study to Be Compulsory in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The French language will be a
compulsory subject in all Nigerian schools starting from the next
session, announced the ministry of education.
</P>
<P>
Director-general of the ministry Alhaji Ibrahim Hashim, while
receiving a delegation from France in capital Abuja on Thursday,
said the government will make sure that adequate teachers and
facilities are in place for French study in the schools.
</P>
<P>
Currently there are 9,000 French language teachers in Nigeria,
but a total of 22,000 are needed if French becomes a compulsory
subject.
</P>
<P>
France has agreed to grant scholarship to about 80 Nigerians
annually to undergo a one-month intensive training in French
language teaching.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian Head of State General Sani Abacha has been personally
advocating French as the second official language of Nigeria
which, surrounded by Francophone west African nations, is
suffering setbacks in ties with its former Anglophone African
allies. 
</P>
