<DOCNO> XIE19970606.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka to Spend 3.19 Billion Dollars on Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh is expected to spend
127.55 billion taka (about 3.19 billion U.S. dollars) for
implementing the new Annual Development Program (ADP) for the next
fiscal year from this July to next June, according to official
sources.
</P>
<P>
The ADP, with 54 percent of the fund coming from the domestic
resources, is to raise the growth of Gross Domestic Product (GDP)
to at least six percent from the current 5.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
It is envisaged that Bangladesh will generate 68.85 billion
taka (about 1.72 billion dollars) from its own resources while the
remaining 53.17 billion taka (about 1.35 billion dollars) will
come as foreign aid and 5.53 billion taka (about 136 million
dollars) from food aid against the Food-for-Work Program.
</P>
<P>
In the current fiscal year's ADP, domestic resources
contributed 67.76 billion taka (about 1.69 billion dollars) and
foreign aid came to 49.24 billion taka (about 1.23 billion
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The budgetary allocation in the new ADP has been earmarked
consistent with the target of the Fifth Five-Year Plan, also to be
launched in July.
</P>
<P>
The Fifth Five-Year Plan has targeted, on average, a 7 percent
GDP growth by implementing its programs, including the ADP.
</P>
<P>
The new ADP, which is to be placed before Parliament on June
12, includes a total of 278 new projects of which 239 are
investment projects and 39 technical assistance. With the
inclusion, the total number of projects in the new ADP for the
fiscal 1997-98 stands at 1,242.
</P>
<P>
Sixty-four projects without budgetary allocation have also been
included in the new ADP for facilitating the negotiation of
foreign fund.
</P>
<P>
The proposed ADP has given utmost emphasis on poverty
eradication and improvement of literacy as part of human resource
development. A total of 41.78 billion taka (about 1.04 billion
dollars) has been earmarked for the social sector.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that over half of its 120 million
people live below the poverty line and only 30 percent can read
and write in this south Asian country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970606.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indiscipline Causes Environment Threat to Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Indisciplined lifestyles and
uncontrolled plunder of natural resources are posing serious threat
to the environment in Nigeria, said Head of State General Sani
Abacha.
</P>
<P>
Abacha, in a message to mark the World Environment Day on
Thursday, promised to step up the government campaign to protect
the environment.
</P>
<P>
He also warned that Nigerians must individually and
collectively retrace their steps to avoid further complication of
the threat.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria is now paying for the errors of past development
activities and indisciplined lifestyles which have devastated the
nation's natural resources, rapidly expanding arid lands,
deserts, erosion and causing urban infrastructural decay, said
the head of state.
</P>
<P>
According to Abacha, the government has promulgated an
environmental impact assessment decree to ensure that
environmental protection measures are adequately considered in
development projects.
</P>
<P>
The Vision 2010, the national body in charge of making
long-term development strategies, has been asked to provide a
"green agenda" to solve environmental problems, said Abacha.
</P>
</TEXT>
