<HEADLINE> Australian Shares Close Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 6 (Xinhua) -- A wave of institutional selling to
fund the take-up of stock in Foster's Brewing Group Ltd drove
Australian shares to a lower close, inflating overall trading
which raced to a record value of more than 2.66 billion Australian
dollars (2.02 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The previous record turnover in dollar terms was set on May 30,
1997 when 1.88 billion Australian dollar worth of stocks was
traded.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index closed 3.3 down at 2,600.9 but
momentarily slipped below the 2,600 barrier just before the close.
</P>
<P>
More than 1.032 billion shares were traded across the board
with falls outnumbering rises 527 to 474.
</P>
<P>
Both BHP and Foster's shares weakened after the mining giant
sold the bulk of its Foster's stake in four swift pre-market
trades.
</P>
<P>
Foster's topped turnover with more than 678.3 million shares
changing hands worth more than 1.689 billion Australian dollars.
Its shares finished seven cents down at 2.53 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
BHP was 11 cents weaker at 18.72 with 3.974 million shares
traded.
</P>
<P>
The trading frenzy followed Thursday's announcement by BHP that
it would end its 11-year link with the brewing group.
</P>
<P>
Traders said the market's overall softness could be attributed
to BHP'S decline.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index sunk 7.8 points to 4,059.4 while the
all resources index inched 0.4 of a point higher to 1,480.7.
</P>
<P>
The gold index was up 10.1 points to 1,559.5 while gold bullion
closed in Sydney at 344.00 US dollars an ounce from 341.35 US
dollars last.
</P>
<P>
Nomura Australia Securities strategist Eric Betts said the
local market was well positioned going into the Queen's Birthday
long weekend.
</P>
<P>
"On the whole the market is well placed ahead of the long
weekend and the release later tonight of the US non-farm payroll
data," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
