<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa, Germany Pledge Further Economic Coop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Top officials of South Africa
and Germany have pledged to promote bilateral existing economic
relations, local daily Sowetan reported today.
</P>
<P>
South African Economic Minister Alec Erwin, who is visiting
Germany, told a joint trade and investment conference in Bonn that
there should be regular economic consultations, including the
participation of companies of the two countries, said the report.
</P>
<P>
German Economic Minister Guenter Rexrodt, who stood for the
proposal, said such meeting would help seeking agreement between
the two countries on all current issues affecting economic
relations.
</P>
<P>
According to Rexrodt, a new investment promotion agreement
between Germany and South Africa is to take effect within the
next few months.
</P>
<P>
Bonn had agreed to guarantee some 35 million U.S. Dollars in
Germany's capital investment in South Africa, while applications
for a further 94 million Dollars are "in pipe line", he said.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Bonn provided guarantees for 761 million Dollars in
German exports to South Africa, adding Germany would also provide
sufficient backing in 1997 as well through the state-owned
insurance company Hermes.
</P>
<P>
The current trade volume between South Africa and Germany
recorded nearly five billion U.S. Dollars with the latter's
capital investment in South Africa registering 1.5 billion
Dollars.
</P>
<P>
South African Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo once described
Germany as a country playing "an outstanding role as a partner of
South Africa."
</P>
<P>
At the moment there are some 300 German companies active in
South Africa, providing 60,000 local jobs, according to official
statistics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
