<DOCNO> XIE19970606.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Irish Voters Cast Ballots in General Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Over 2.7 million people across the
Republic of Ireland began to cast their ballots this morning in
the country's general election, press reports from Dublin said.
</P>
<P>
The ruling three-party coalition of the Fine Gael, Labor, and
Democratic Left, the opposition alliance of the Fianna Fail and
Progressive Democrats, and some other smaller political parties
will battle for the 166 seats of the Dail (the lower house of the
Irish parliament) in 44 constituencies all over the country.
</P>
<P>
Opinion polls indicate that Prime Minister John Bruton's
coalition government has been consistently trailed the main
opposition alliance in public support. The opposition alliance is
tipped to win the election.
</P>
<P>
No Irish government has won an re-election since 1969, but
Prime Minister Bruton has vowed to win over the 14-percent
undecided voters in a bid to turn the tables.
</P>
<P>
Ireland's general election is held under a proportional
representation system, which is widely regarded as
favorable to smaller parties.
</P>
<P>
The turn-out in the 1992 election was 68.5 percent.
Fianna Fail, the country's largest political party, took 68
seats of the 166-seated Dail, Fine Gael 45, Labor 33, the
Progressive Democrats 10, Democratic Left four and other
six. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970606.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Chinese People's Life in The Fast Lane (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Liang Xingfa, a salesman for a
township enterprise in suburban Shanghai, notes with pleasure that
China's trains run faster than ever. "Sleeping over a night in the
cabin, I can talk businesses the next morning in Beijing," he said.
</P>
<P>
Cindy Wang, an event planner of US Intel (China) Ltd., however,
still prefers to take plane for business trips. "Speed is vital
for our company. Not just the speed of our microprocessors, but
also the speed to introduce them into the market," she said. "To
timely present the latest products, I fly over most parts of China
this year."
</P>
<P>
Fan Zhongcheng, a professor of Qinghua University, links up
with the outer world in faster way. With a desktop computer and a
modem, he keeps almost instant contact with academic circles
worldwide. "Really, it's as late Chairman Mao said in a
poem: 'It's a tour lasting 80,000 li/Even though you sit still.'"
(Li is a Chinese distance measurement equivalent to 500 meters.)
</P>
<P>
The moderization drive is speeding up the pace of millions of
Chinese lives. The transport and telecom industries, once
bottlenecks, have become boosters of China's economy.
</P>
<P>
Now the trunk rail lines in China run at a speed of 140
kilometers an hour. The Beijing-Guangzhou Express, hurtling
one-way down China's busiest arterial railway, has had six hours
shaved off its time, a fifth less than before.
</P>
<P>
China's aviation industry witnessed more than 20 percent yearly
growth after the 1980s. The passenger traffic volume last year
topped 56.5 million.
</P>
<P>
The telecom authorities has set the target each year to add 14
million lines for new telephone users until the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Internet has boomed in popularity in China from zero to more
than 150,000 registered individuals in cyberspace.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970606.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Chinese People's Life in the Fast Lane (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Speed has had, without precedent, a deep impact on different
aspects of life for a gigantic number of people," a local
economist said.
</P>
<P>
Profound changes have occurred in China's vast rural areas,
where time had been measured by sunrise and sunset for
centuries. Old animal-driven carts have been replaced by motorized
farm vehicles. Farmers in developed areas, who years ago had
nothing but spades and sickles in their hands, now use mobile
phones to conduct business or manage farmland with the aid of
computers.
</P>
<P>
Changes in urban areas also have altered certain fundamental
ways of living, such as eating. Chinese- or foreign-style
fast-food restaurants have spread nationwide. But, one frequent
fast-food patron admits he goes "not for the taste, but for saving
time".
</P>
<P>
Other services speeding the pace of life include freight
couriers, express mail, telephone shopping, and on-line ordering.
</P>
<P>
Government organs have also made efforts to appear more
efficient. Seven government departments in Beijing, such as
industry and commerce administration, custom house, and taxation
organ, early this year organized a unified annual check-up for
ventures with overseas investment. The one-office-for-all method
was acclaimed an effective way to reduce the workload of the
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Social researchers have scrutinized the changes intensely.
</P>
<P>
"The economic goals set by the country determined that
high-speed development is an essential requirement to reach the
targets," said a sociologist with China Academy of Social Sciences.
</P>
<P>
"Even though China has quadrupled its gross national product
ahead of the schedule, the country has to keep around 9-percent
growth in the ensuing years for its second strategic goal -- to
become a medium-level developed country in the mid-21st century,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Another expert said that "The world is changing. To keep pace
with global trends, China has to change even faster while
overcoming the rigidness of its past system."
</P>
<P>
All experts agreed that the faster pace of life is an
illustration of social progress in the country. As one expert put
it: "The further development of China's modernization will
definitely accelerate the pace of life in the future." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970606.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
