<DOCNO> XIE19970606.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAU Summit Very Successful, Mkapa Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 6 (Xinhua) -- President Benjamin Mkapa on
Thursday said the just ended OAU Summit in Harare, Zimbabwe, was
very successful endorsing important political and economic
decisions.
</P>
<P>
Outlining his impressions on the three-day summit, President
Mkapa said in Dar es Salaam that beside adopting key resolutions,
the meeting was attended by more African leaders than any other
such OAU gathering in the organisation's history.
</P>
<P>
According to a press release issued by the State House in the
city, the president said that one of the historical
pronouncements by the Heads of State was the condemnation of the
Sierra Leone coup which overthrew a popularly-elected government,
saying the act was not acceptable in today's Africa.
</P>
<P>
He said it was evident that African leaders no longer approve
suppressive regimes and the endless conflicts in the continent.
</P>
<P>
That is why, Mkapa said, the leaders resolved to restore the
overthrown government by every possible means.
</P>
<P>
Another achievement of the Harare meeting, the president said, was
the resolve to form the African Economic Community under the Abuja OAU
resolution.
</P>
<P>
For the first time in history the leaders met as the first
African Economic Community Summit to discuss regional reports of
regional economic groupings like the SADC, IGAD, ECOWAS, COMESA
and Maghreb, he added.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa said the regional economic groupings were instrumental
in boosting Africa's economic might.
</P>
<P>
"African countries have for the first time stated
categorically that they were now interested in economic
liberation having completed the liberation of the continent from
colonial rule," the president stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970606.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France, U.S. Opposed Downlisting of Ivory Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 6 (Xinhua) -- France and the United States both
strongly opposed to the bid by southern African countries to
allow limited trade in ivory, but might consider solutions for
the specific problems of Zimbabwe, Botswana and Namibia.
</P>
<P>
The French government has made clear its position that
elephants, classified as endangered species, remain in Appendix I
of the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species
(CITES) which does not allow any trade in ivory.
</P>
<P>
"Normally the French government would wish that the elephants
remain in Appendix I to avoid liberalizing of ivory trade because
the situation of elephants on the continent is heterogeneous,"
said a spokesman of the French Embassy in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe, which is hosting the 10th CITES conference from June
9 to 20, have been campaigning hard with Botswana and Namibia for
downlisting elephants from Appendix I to Appendix II which allows
controlled trade.
</P>
<P>
"The situation in west Africa regarding elephants is different
but France is open to discuss the specific problems of southern
African region," said the French embassy spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The United States said it was firmly opposed to the bid to
open ivory trade saying this risked the remaining elephant
populations on the continent.
</P>
<P>
European diplomat in Harare also supported the idea that the
ban on ivory trade be maintained though many countries will have
an open attitude about the problems in Zimbabwe, Botswana and
Namibia.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe, Botswana and Namibia need support from two-thirds of
the CITES members to get their elephant populations off the
endangered species list, which they have tried to do without
success at the last three CITES meetings since 1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970606.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Donates Sniffer Dogs to Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Development Program (UNDP)
has donated four sniffer dogs to Zambia to help it fight drug
trafficking.
</P>
<P>
UNDP handed over the dogs to the country's Drug Enforcement
Commission (DEC) at the Lusaka international airport on Wednesday
after they arrived at the airport from South Africa, where they
attended training, according to Times of Zambia.
</P>
<P>
UNDP resident representative Gary Davis said during a brief
ceremony that "these dogs were trained under the U.N. dog control
program. It is a continued program to help fight drug trafficking
in the region."
</P>
<P>
DEC commissioner Raphael Mungole said the dogs will be
stationed at the airport together with three Zambian special dogs
that graduated from South African police dog training school.
</P>
<P>
Plans are underway to acquire more dogs to be deployed in all
border posts of the country, said the DEC official. 
</P>
</TEXT>
