<DOCNO> XIE19970606.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, June 6 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The United States and Israel have voiced their
concerns about Iran's military build-up, a threat to regional
countries, during their strategic talks here. A Defense Ministry
statement said that the two sides spent a good deal of time
discussing regional terrorism and efforts by Iran to arm itself,
particularly with long-range missiles and non-conventional
weapons.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Rebels of the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK)
kidnaped eight workers late Thursday night in southeastern
Turkey, the semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported this
morning. The Turkish security forces started large-scale search
operations in the region in a bid to capture the PKK kidnapers,
said the agency.
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali Alatas announced
here today that his country has decided to cancel its planned
purchase of nine F-16 planes from the U.S. government. Alatas said
his government has also decided to forgo its participation in the
Expanded International Military Education and Training (E-IMET)
program offered by the U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
YANGON -- Myanmar officials and a German business group held a
meeting here Thursday on the promotion of economic cooperation
between the two countries. Myanmar officials and Siemens AG group
discussed a hydro-power project, electricity generation and
supply, communications, the repair and purchase of locomotives and
the purchase of medicines and medical equipment, the report said.
</P>
<P>
LISBON -- In the run-up to Hong Kong's return to China, a photo
show entitled "The Present and Future of Hong Kong" was opened
here today. On display are 88 photos, reflecting the history of
Hong Kong, the patriotism of Hong Kong people and their confidence
in future stability and prosperity of Hong Kong after its return
to the motherland.
</P>
<P>
ROME -- Thousands of artifacts, paintings, statues and bronzes
robbed from archeological sites and private homes worth five
billion lire (about 3 million U.S. dollars) have been recovered by
police after they smashed a ring of art thieves operating between
Italy and Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Revoking normal trade relations with China would
do harm to U.S. strategic interests and Isolate the United States,
Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin warned on Thursday. "Severing
trade ties with China will not isolate China. It will isolate the
United States. It will also lead other nations in Asia to question
our commitment to the region," he said.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Although the U.S. economy is in the strongest
growth in a decade and the unemployment rate the lowest in a
quarter-century, many people were left behind and have a hard time
to find a job. In the District of Columbia, the U.S. capital, the
jobless rate averaged 7.6 percent in the past four months.
</P>
</TEXT>
