<HEADLINE> Northwest China to Open up More Wasteland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region
in Northwest China plans to turn another 300,000 ha of wasteland
into green fields in the next three years, in its continuing
efforts to promote agricultural development.
</P>
<P>
The ethnic region has cultivated 210,000 ha of wasteland over
the past five years to become China's largest cotton producer and
an important grain production base.
</P>
<P>
Xinjiang covers an area of 1.66 million sq km, accounting for
one-sixth of the country, and has about 4.86 million ha of arable
wasteland, which is expected to partly ease China's grain shortage
in the next century.
</P>
<P>
Local farmers from various ethnic groups still remain the
driving force in cultivating wasteland. One farmer in the Tarim
Basin has opened up more than 1,300 ha of wasteland.
</P>
<P>
Governments, enterprises, and overseas investors have also
joined the campaign. The State and localities have put more than a
billion yuan into the development of Xinjiang's water and soil in
recent years, while Chinese and overseas enterprises have invested
400 million yuan for the same purposes.
</P>
<P>
To encourage wasteland improvement, the region has adopted some
preferential policies, including interest-free and low-interest
loans, and longer leasing time for land use.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
