<HEADLINE> PKK Kidnaps 8 Workers in Southeastern Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Rebels of the outlawed Kurdish
Workers' Party (PKK) kidnaped eight workers late Thursday night
in southeastern Turkey, the semi-official Anatolia News Agency
reported this morning.
</P>
<P>
The agency said that a group of the PKK militants
gathered the workers in Dilimli Dam construction site near
Yuksekova-Esendere highway of Hakkari province bordering Iran at
about 23:00 local time (20:00 GMT) and took them away in the
dark.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish security forces started large-scale search
operations in the region in a bid to capture the PKK kidnapers,
said the agency.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, the agency said that the Turkish
security forces killed 14 PKK members in Kocacimen village of
Kemaliye town, eastern province of Erzican Thursday.
</P>
<P>
One police soldier also died in the five-hour-long conflict,
said the agency.
</P>
<P>
In another development, some PKK guerrillas attacked Yalinca
Gendarma station in Gurpinar town of Van province bordering Iran
at 23:00 local time (20:00 GMT) Wednesday and one police
soldier died in the armed clash between the PKK and Turkish
soldiers, said the agency.
</P>
<P>
It added that one PKK member was also killed in the
30-minute-long clash.
</P>
<P>
About 50,000-strong Turkish government troops have carried out
cross-border military operations in northern Iraq since May 14
to wipe out the PKK establishment there.
</P>
<P>
Turkish military officials have said that at least 2,000
PKK members have been killed in the military campaign in
northern Iraq, but the PKK claimed that its losses were less
than 100 people.
</P>
<P>
Khalil Attachi, leader of the PKK was quoted by a
newspaper as saying in Lebanon Monday that his group will
attack Israeli and U.S. targets in Turkish cities and tourist
areas.
</P>
<P>
Attachi said that his organization will "carry out operations
against Israeli targets in Istanbul (Turkey's largest city) and
elsewhere in Turkey and against the U.S. enemy interests."
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting an almost 13-year-old separatist
war for autonomy, which has claimed over 23,000 lives in
eastern and southeastern Turkey since August 1984.
</P>
</TEXT>
