<DOCNO> XIE19970606.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's First Quarter Gold Demand Sets New Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Demand for gold in India set a
new quarterly record when it reached 161.70 tons in the first
quarter of 1997.
</P>
<P>
This was up by 38 percent from the corresponding period a year
ago and 12 percent ahead of the previous record of 143.90 tons,
said the latest quarterly study by the World Gold Council (WGC).
</P>
<P>
Gold imports into India during the first quarter of this year
have reached a record of 116.90 tons, well above the quarterly
record of 76 tons set in the fourth quarter of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The recent moves on the part of the Indian government to
liberalize the trade in gold will lead to increased legal imports,
away from the unofficial or parallel supplies of the yellow metal,
the WGC study said.
</P>
<P>
India is one of the world's fastest growing jewelry centers and
is becoming an important destination on the itineraries of jewelry
buyers the world over.
</P>
<P>
The process of accelerated deregulation in India following the
Delhi gold economic conference in November 1996 and the doubling
of import allowances to 10 kg for non-resident Indians will
encourage more companies to import gold and pave the way for
further improvements in distribution and domestic demand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
