<HEADLINE> North China Using Overseas Talents in Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Technical advice from Japanese
experts has helped farmers in Shunping County of north China's
Hebei Province earn 370 yuan more per capita from their apple
crops.
</P>
<P>
The county imported a high-quality variety of Japanese apple in
the early 1980s, but poor management led to low yields. Soon
after, the county authorities invited Japanese experts to guide
the cultivation.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the production rate of high quality apples has
been raised from 30 percent to 70 percent. In same cases, the
per-ha apple output is as high as 60,000 to 75,000 kg.
</P>
<P>
Shunping is just one example of a foreign expert-assisted
project with a happy ending: Hebei has so far launched more than
260 programs to bring in overseas professionals in various fields,
which has helped resolve 152 technical difficulties in
agricultural production, develop 110 new products, and bring about
650 million yuan in economic profit.
</P>
<P>
The province sent more than 300 students or scholars abroad,
and some who have returned from the United States have applied a
detoxification technique to 80 percent of Hebei's strawberry
seedlings, reporting good results.
</P>
<P>
Hebei recently signed agriculture agreements with five European
countries to conduct technical and personnel exchanges. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
