<DOCNO> XIE19970606.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, Germany Join Hands in Fighting Desertification </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, June 6 (Xinhua) -- On a historical ancient battlefield
covering Shanxi Province and the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region,
forestry experts from China and Germany are fighting
desertification shoulder to shoulder with unusual weapons: poplar
trees.
</P>
<P>
Local people have planted many poplar trees in the area since
New China was founded in 1949. But the small-leaf poplars cannot
adapt to the harsh weather there, and wither in only 20 years.
</P>
<P>
In 1984, a new forestry project was launched. Unlike previous
programs, 10.6 million German marks worth of free aid from Germany
was involved in the effort.
</P>
<P>
Since 1984, modern labs have been set up in the area and
advanced facilities introduced from overseas. So far, technicians
have collected nearly 1,000 varieties of poplars and set up the
largest poplar gene bank in the country.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, 35 species of poplar trees that grow rapidly
and are better able to withstand cold weather and wind have been
developed. Test forests of various types were planted, where the
survival rate of the trees were increased by ten to 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
The various poplar species and technology to grow them have
been introduced to other parts of northern China and shown
profitable results, according to officials in charge of the
cooperation project.
</P>
<P>
In May of 1996 a decision was made by the Sino-German committee
to extend the project by three years. Another three million German
Marks will be put into the work. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970606.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
