<DOCNO> XIE19970606.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 07:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-up: Netanyahu Plan on Final Settlement Draws </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The plan proposed by Prime
Minister Binyamin Netanyahu on the final Israeli-Palestinian
settlement has triggered mixed reactions across Israel's political
spectrum.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu presented his proposal Wednesday to the inner
cabinet for discussion. The Prime Minister's Office called it
as the "Allon-Plus" plan, because it is an enlarged version
of the original formula proposed by late Foreign Minister
Yigal Allon after the 1967 war.
</P>
<P>
In the plan, Netanyahu envisioned retaining control over the
strategic borders, Greater Jerusalem, settlements, water resources
and key roads in the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
The disclosure of the plan has caused strong condemnation from
the Palestinian National Authority (PNA), which denounced it for
violating the Oslo accords and warned against leading to violent
confrontation.
</P>
<P>
Back in Israel, the plan also aroused a controversy within
the political spectrum as political factions differed in their
opinions on the Israeli-Palestinian final-status talks.
</P>
<P>
In a sudden burst of dissent, Foreign Minister David Levy
criticized the plan as a premature disclosure made without
prior consulation with other cabinet ministers.
</P>
<P>
Interviewed by state television Channel I Thursday night,
Levy insisted the plan was only "preliminary, embryonic ideas"
and not a cabinet decision. He added that the disclosure
could cause damage to Israel's negotiating stance in future
final-status talks.
</P>
<P>
"As long as these ideas (by different ministers) have not
crystallized and the deliberations still are in their earliest
stage, circulation of these notions only can cause harm," he
said.
</P>
<P>
But the center-rightist party The Third Way, a coalition
partner, praised the disclosure of the Netanyahu plan. A party
statement called it as "a move by the prime minister toward
the responsible and moderate center, while adopting our party's
political-defense map."
</P>
<P>
The Third Way also called Ehud Barak, the newly-elected
leader of the leading opposition Labor party, to support the
plan.
</P>
<P>
However, the Meretz party, Labor's traditional political ally,
condemned the plan as "a bad joke." Meretz leader Yossi
Sarid warned the Labor against accepting the plan, saying he
would not hesitate in distancing his party from the Labor in
that case.
</P>
<P>
"Any plan which does not ultimately call for a Palestinian
state and a withdrawal from most of the territories will not
hold water and is likely to hold blood, lots of blood,"
Sarid said.
</P>
<P>
The Netanyahu plan also came under fire from the extremist
rightist party Moledet, which denounced Netanyahu for going
toward the left. Moledet leader Rehavam Zeevi expressed concern
that Netanyahu would eventually agree to the establishment of
a Palestinian state and surrender of most of the territories.
</P>
<P>
The rightist National Religious Party (NRP), a coalition
partner, reacted cautiously to the Netanyahu plan. Hanan Porat,
chairman of the NRP faction in the Knesset (parliament), said
his party would not leave the government at present because
of the Netanyahu plan.
</P>
<P>
But Porat made it clear that his party would not allow
the government to uproot even a single settlement in the
Palestinian territories. The NRP can easily topple the Netanyahu
government because it owns 9 Knesset seats.
</P>
<P>
By presenting his plan on the final-status talks, which
have been frozen since early last year, Netanyahu is
apparently sending out a test balloon pending the resamption
of the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The final-status talks will tackle the most sensitive and
difficult issues of the final borders, status of Jerusalem and
Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
Under the Netanyahu plan, the PNA could only get about 40
percent of the West Bank and Gaza Strip, which is much
less than the 90 percent it has required in the final
settlement.
</P>
<P>
The PNA is hoping to create an independent state on most
of the territories with East Jerusalem as capital after
reaching the final settlement, a scenario that has been flatly
rejected by the hardline Netanyahu government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970606.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Wildlife Experts Want One Voice on CITES </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Over 80 experts from 33 African
countries attended a two-day meeting to prepare for the 10th
Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species (CITES)
conference which begins in Zimbabwe's capital Harare on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Opening the preparatory dialogue in Darwendale, a suburban
town near Harare yesterday, Zimbabwean Minister of Environment
and Tourism Chen Chimutengwende called on African countries to
speak with one voice at the forthcoming cites meeting, if their
proposals were to be accepted.
</P>
<P>
Botswana, Namibia and Zimbabwe are currently lobbying for
support for the downlisting of the African elephant from CITES
Appendix I to Appendix II, which allows limited trade in the
mammal products.
</P>
<P>
They request for the lift of the trade ban, put in place in
1989, to enable them to dispose ivory stockpiles worth several
millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania, Uganda and Madagascar are requesting for the
downlisting of the crocodile, and South Africa is advocating for
the downlisting of the white rhino.
</P>
<P>
"It is my fervent hope that you will speak as Africans with a
common purpose in the same way people from other continents do,"
said the Zimbabwean minister.
</P>
<P>
The World Conservation Union, organizer and sponsor of the
meeting, also backed the Zimbabwean government's proposal to
downlist the African elephant to allow limited international
ivory trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
