<HEADLINE> Combat Against Narcotics Effective in Yunnan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, June 6 (Xinhua) -- During April and May, police in
southwest China's border province of Yunnan cracked 1,371 drug
trafficking cases and seized 1,830 drug traffickers.
</P>
<P>
In the two months, a total of 994.8 kg of opium and heroin was
seized, according to Sun Dahong, secretary-general of the Yunnan
Anti-Drug Commission.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has decided to carry out a special
nationwide anti-drug campaign from April to September.
</P>
<P>
Yunnan Province, located next to Vietnam, Myanmar and Laos,
sharing 4,060 km of borders with these countries, plays a key role
in fighting against international drug-trafficking.
</P>
<P>
Sun also said that in the two months, more than 7,600 narcotics
users received compulsory treatment.
</P>
<P>
To check the influx of narcotics, an anti-drug headquarters
commanded by the provincial governor was set up in early April.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government set aside ten million yuan (1.2
million US dollars) for the rehabilitation of drug users, and
lower-level governments all provided supporting funds.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government has also exerted great efforts to
mobilize the masses in the fight against drug trafficking and
narcotics consumption.
</P>
<P>
From tips and informants from the masses, 49 drug trafficking
cases were cracked in April and May, and 36 kg of opium and heroin
were seized.
</P>
<P>
Provincial officials said the anti-drug combat will be stepped
up in June to further diminish the influx of narcotics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
