<DOCNO> XIE19970606.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangdong-HK Shuttle-Bus Service Booms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Every morning, Hong Kong
businessman Wong Wiu Kwong catches the Guangdong-Hong Kong shuttle
at a local hotel in Guangzhou, the capital city of Guangdong
Province.
</P>
<P>
Throughout the ride, Wong relaxes in the air-conditioning,
watches TV, and enjoys the free beverages and newspapers provided
to passengers.
</P>
<P>
"Traveling had not been so convenient before this kind of bus
began operation," he recalled. "Before, I had to first take a
train or a ship and then change to a bus."
</P>
<P>
Wong is among tens of thousands people who have benefited from
the fledgling shuttle bus service which links Hong Kong with urban
and rural areas in Guangdong Province. The number of people
traveling between the two places exceeds 60 million annully.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is the largest investor in Guangdong; nearly 80
percent of processing factories in Hong Kong have been moved to
Guangdong in recent years. Hong Kong-based investors have been
involved in over 80,000 firms in the neighboring province.
</P>
<P>
In 1981, the first such shuttle-bus was put into use by the
Guangdong-Hong Kong Automotive Transport Company, and to date over
500 shuttle-buses, owned by 65 local firms, are engaged in the
lucrative business. More than 30,000 passengers travel on these
buses every day.
</P>
<P>
The growth of the shuttle-bus service has been made possible by
the rapid expansion of expressways, officials from the provincial
communications authority said.
</P>
<P>
The latest statistics show that Guangdong now has 723 km of
freeways, ranking first among all provinces and municipalities in
the country. Moreover, the province plans to construct another 10
expressways with a total length of over 1,000 km.
</P>
<P>
By then, all the major cities and towns in Guangdong will have
access to expressways.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the increasingly competitive market has also brought
down the price of a Guangzhou-Hong Kong shuttle ticket from an
average of 250 yuan to the current price of 150 yuan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
