<HEADLINE> Number of Japanese Traveling Abroad Hits Record High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 6 (Xinhua) -- A record 16.69 million Japanese
traveled abroad in 1996 despite the weaker yen, according to a
government white paper on tourism released today.
</P>
<P>
The figure was up 1.4 million from the previous year, the paper
said. Of the 16.69 million, 13.77 million were tourists.
</P>
<P>
The most popular destination for Japanese travelers was the
United States, with 5.18 million, followed by Hong Kong with 1.51
million, South Korea with 1.44 million, China's mainland with 1.02
million and Taiwan with 830,000, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the number of foreigners who visited Japan in 1996
totaled 3.48 million, up 490,000 over the previous year, the paper
said.
</P>
<P>
The deficit in Japan's international travel account in
1996 increased to 4.45 trillion yen (38.7 billion dollars), up 486
billion yen (4.2 billion dollars) from 1995, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
