<HEADLINE> Shandong Spreads Use of Paper Boxes in Catering Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, June 6 (Xinhua) -- East China's Shandong Province,
China's second most populous province, will replace the widely
used styrofoamed snack boxes with boxes made of paper.
</P>
<P>
Zhao Shili, head of the provincial epidemic prevention station,
said paper-made snack boxes will be required to be used in
restaurants, snack bars, railway, airlines, and enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Disposable styrofoam boxes may discharge polluted gas after
burning and they can cause serious "white pollution" problem, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Shandong has 17 cities. It is predicted that the 10,000
restaurants and snack bars in the provincial capital of Jinan
alone could use 500,000 styrofoamed boxes a day.
</P>
<P>
The province has now established six paper box factories.
</P>
<P>
A number of Chinese cities including Harbin, Wuhan and Hangzhou
have banned the use of styrofoamed boxes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
