<HEADLINE> Israel US Holds Strategic Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 6 (Xinhua) -- In their strategic talks, the
United States and Israel have voiced their concerns about Iran's
military build-up, a threat to regional countries.
</P>
<P>
According to the pro-government English daily, The Jerusalem
Post, today, the two-day biannual U.S.-Israel strategic talks
ended in Natanya, north of Tel Aviv, Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A Defense Ministry statement said that the two sides spent a
good deal of time discussing regional terrorism and efforts by
Iran to arm itself, particularly with long-range missiles and
non-conventional weapons. They also discussed assessments of the
general situation in the region.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources said the U.S. and Israel see eye to eye on
what they believe the potential military threat posed by Iran to
almost all of its neighboring states.
</P>
<P>
Iran was described as a threat to the former Soviet republics
of Central Asia, the Arab emirates of the Gulf, Saudi Arabia, and
Israel. Also taken into account was Iran's ongoing logistical
support for Lebanon's Hezbollah guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
There was a consensus in their discussions on the need to
maintain economic sanctions against Iran and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli delegation was led by David Ivry, special adviser
to Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai, while the U.S. was
represented by Ted MacNamara, Assistant Secretary of State.
</P>
<P>
Working teams presented reports on joint exercises, logistics,
and other areas of cooperation between the defense establishments
of the two allies. The U.S. officials also reiterated
Washington's promise to maintain Israel's military "qualitative
edge" in the future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
