<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Animal Husbandry Keeps Grain Price Stable in East China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Animal husbandry in east China's
Shandong Province has become a major contributor to the steady
growth of grain production, as it consumes and increases value of
nearly half the total grain output annually.
</P>
<P>
The province has no grassland, but it has grown into the
largest livestock producer in China. And the 140-million-tons of
manure from livestock helped produce the province's 43.3 billion
kg of grain last year.
</P>
<P>
It had had 14.5 million of cattle and 49.1 million of sheep by
the end of last year, both ranking first in the country. Livestock
farming eats up more than 30 million tons of farmers' straw,
accounting for 60 percent of the total amount.
</P>
<P>
Livestock raising resulted in maize price hikes last year, and
as a result, the province imported large amounts of maize to meet
the need.
</P>
<P>
As growing animal husbandry demands more grains, it helps
maintain grain prices, which encourages farmers to grow more
crops. Industry insiders call animal husbandry the "stabilizer" of
Shandong's grain production. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970606.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1,700-year-old Wooden And Bamboo Slips Well Preserved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Chinese experts have discovered
why tens of thousands of pieces of bamboo and wood, strung
together to form a book, have been preserved for some 1,700 years
in a well in this capital of central China's Hunan Province.
</P>
<P>
"The well served as an 'underground refrigerator', maintaining
a constant temperature that helped conserve the slips," the
experts say.
</P>
<P>
The well, found at a construction site, has a diameter of three
meters. The inner wall of the well was lined with wooden boards,
and chinked with clay.
</P>
<P>
At the bottom of the well was a smaller square pit to retain
underground water, which could be ladled out if the pit was full.
Straw mats were placed between the bottom of the well and the wood
and bamboo slips.
</P>
<P>
Some 170,000 bamboo and wooden slips bearing 200,000 Chinese
characters were stored in the well, the largest such find ever
reported in the country.
</P>
<P>
The slips record in detail the political, economic, military,
cultural and geographic situation of Changsha prefecture under the
Wu State (222-280) during the Three Kingdoms Period (220-280).
</P>
<P>
The well was actually a cellar which served as a storage space
for archives of the Changsha prefecture at that time, the experts
say.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970606.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Exchange Trade Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 6 (Xinhua) -- In May, the foreign currencies
transaction volume at the China Foreign Exchange Trading Center
was equivalent to 5.86 billion US dollars, up 22 percent compared
with the previous month.
</P>
<P>
According to the center, in the 21 trading days of the month,
5.46 billion US dollars, 2.54 billion HK dollars, and 9.17 billion
Japanese yen were traded.
</P>
<P>
Chinese yuan went down slightly against US dollar, from April's
8.2945 to 8.2921, while the rate between yuan and HK remained the
same as the previous month.
</P>
<P>
Affected by a strong yen in the international market, one yuan
was equivalent to 7.1182 yen on May 30, up 0.5871 against the
figure of the previous month.
</P>
<P>
The center is located in Shanghai. It began operation in April
1994 and trades every trading day in the morning. The rates are
published by the People's Bank of China, the central bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
