<HEADLINE> Kohl Thanks U.S. for Marshall Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 5 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl
paid a one-day visit to the United States to formally thank the
country for its help in rebuilding Europe after World War II.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a wreath-laying ceremony for former Secretary of
State George Marshall, architect of the post-war European recovery
plan, at Arlington National Cemetery, Kohl said the massive aid
program had set Europe on a course of peace and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that maintaining the transatlantic alliance between
Europe and the U.S. remained crucial to Germany and all of Europe.
</P>
<P>
"To us Germans, the trans-Atlantic partnership...is one of the
greatest achievement in our history," Kohl added.
</P>
<P>
He said that Germany is and will be "forever thankful to the
American people."
</P>
<P>
The chancellor's 24-hour visit to Washington was seen as
reaffirming the vital and close ties between the two countries as
differences are increasing after the end of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
Germany and the U.S. have differed publicly over how to develop
relations with Iran, and the German restriction of the Church of
Scientology. 
