<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia-Pacific Roundtable Opens in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The 11th Asia-Pacific
Roundtable (APR) conference opened here today to address
prevailing and future security issues in the region.
</P>
<P>
The annual APR in Malaysia this year is part of a continuing
series on the theme "Confidence Building and Conflict Reduction in
the Pacific."
</P>
<P>
Delivering a keynote address at the opening of the three-day
conference, Malaysian Acting Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim said
prosperity has much to do with security and part of the impetus
for strengthening what is called the Pacific peace comes from the
need to foster Pacific prosperity cooperatively.
</P>
<P>
"Shared prosperity promotes peace and stability. It fosters the
social and political environment for the cultivation of civil
society," he said.
</P>
<P>
He outlined three objectives for the Pacific nations to focus
on in the next 25 years.
</P>
<P>
The objectives are "maximize mutual understanding," "strengthen
mutual respect and appreciation" and "foster mutual cultural
enrichment."
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian leader was of the view that mutual understanding
and mutual respect are the beginning of mutual trust.
</P>
<P>
Cultures and civilizations should not divide, on the contrary,
they should arouse interest and spur exchange, he said, adding,
"We of the Pacific must reject, and reject most vigorously, the
thesis that civilizations are destined to collide, especially in
this part of the world."
</P>
<P>
He said that as technology and trade telescope geography and
obliterate borders and as civil society takes root within states
and forges links across boundaries, the imperative to foster
cooperation, mutual understanding and friendship among the peoples
of the Pacific becomes ever more demanding and urgent.
</P>
<P>
"It is time to proceed with the massive building of the bridges
of friendship and understanding not only between governments, not
only between the military and the security agencies, but also

