<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Cancel Purchase of F-16s From U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali
Alatas announced here today that his country has decided to cancel
its planned purchase of nine F-16 planes from the U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
Talking to reporters at a Foreign Ministry news briefing,
Alatas said the Indonesian government has also decided to forego
its participation in the Expanded International Military Education
and Training (E-IMET) program offered by the U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
According to Alatas, in a letter dated May 26, 1997, Indonesian
President Seoharto informed U.S. President Bill Clinton of the
decision and cited "wholly unjustified criticism" of Indonesia in
the U.S. Congress as one of the factors that led to this decision.
</P>
<P>
In the letter, Soeharto stressed that the decision was taken
with but one goal in mind, namely to remove any possible stumbling
block that could come in the way of efforts by both countries to
expand and enhance their relationship or that could cause
difficulties to the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
With the linkage removed between criticism of Indonesia and its
participation in IMET and the projected purchase of F-16 planes,
the president said, "the relationship between the United States
and Indonesia would move forward to a new and even sounder level
of cooperation based on mutual respect, mutual benefit and
non-interference in each other's domestic affairs."
</P>
<P>
Indonesia has purchased 12 F-16s from the United States but the
sale of the remaining nine the U.S. promised to Indonesia two
years ago has been delayed several times because of human rights
concerns from some members of the U.S. Congress.
</P>
<P>
Alatas said the Indonesian government's decision will not
affect the relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
"At present, our relations are very good," he declared.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970606.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
