<HEADLINE> Myanmar, Thailand to Jointly Build Sugar Mill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar and Thailand have signed a
joint venture contract to build a 2,000-ton sugar mill in Pyay
area of Bago division, adjacent to Yangon, to develop the
country's sugar industry.
</P>
<P>
Official paper The New Light of Myanmar said today that the
land lease contract to build the joint-venture sugar mill was
reached here Thursday between the Sugarcane Enterprise of
Myanmar's Ministry of Agriculture and Irrigation and Thailand's
Sutech Engineering Co Ltd.
</P>
<P>
Increased production of sugarcane along with other economically
important crops such as cotton, rubber and coffee, will facilitate
the diversification of agricultural sector in Myanmar, the paper
said, quoting Minister Lieutenant-General Myint Aung.
</P>
<P>
The minister also disclosed at the signing ceremony that his
ministry has already signed contracts for two 1,500-ton sugar
mills with the Guangdong Zhuhai Corporation, a Chinese firm.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest official statistics, Thailand's
investment in Myanmar ranks third after Britain and Singapore with
1.02 billion U.S. dollars in 39 permitted projects out of the
total foreign investment of over six billion U.S. dollars at the
end of March this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
