<DOCNO> XIE19970606.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Electoral System Proposed in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan Minister of
Constitutional Affairs G.L. Peiris on Thursday presented a new
electoral system to the Parliamentary Select Committee (PSC).
</P>
<P>
Peiris described the new system as a simple electoral system
that makes Parliament reflect the wishes of the people, parliament
sources said today.
</P>
<P>
The proposed electoral system combines the territorial and
proportional representation (PR) systems and will do away with
preferential voting which confused voters and caused rivalry
within parties.
</P>
<P>
According to the proposal, the government will consist of 198
members of parliament, half of who will be elected territorially
on the first-past-the-post basis and the other half under the PR
system, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Recognized political parties, independent groups and
individuals can contest the territorial seats. Votes cast for
political parties and independent groups will be computed on a
regional basis to determine the PR representation of each party or
independent group.
</P>
<P>
Political parties and independent groups must submit lists of
candidates to be selected under the PR system. The decision to
determine the persons to represent the party will rest with the
secretary of the party concerned.
</P>
<P>
The new proposals also provide for the creation of multiple
constituencies to ensure representation of minority groups or
interests.
</P>
<P>
The PSC will meet on June 13 for a detailed consideration of
the new proposal.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970606.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GM Sets up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 6 (Xinhua) -- General Motors and the Shanghai
Automotive Industry Corporation have agreed to develop a major
automotive development center in the Pudong New Area of Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
The two will set up the Shanghai GM Company Ltd. and the
Pan-Asia Automotive Technological Center Company Ltd., the
largest-ever Sino-US joint venture in a bid to turn Shanghai into
a major automotive development center in Asia.
</P>
<P>
The project will cost 1.57 billion US dollars. The Shanghai
Automotive Industry Corporation and the US-based General
Motors each hold 50 percent of the stake.
</P>
<P>
The joint venture will produce GM "Buick" cars of the 1997's
fashion as the first generation product, which is expected to be
put on the market by the end of 1998 or early 1999. Meanwhile,
efforts will be made to design a second model.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the General Motors, one of the largest car
manufacturer in the world, has invested nearly 350 million US
dollars to build up 12 joint ventures in China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
