<DOCNO> XIE19970606.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Farmers in Nepal Face Shortage of Fertilizers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Nepali farmers are facing a
severe shortage of fertilizers this year mainly due to the
decrease in governmental grant assistance, agriculture officials
said here today.
</P>
<P>
Only one third of the farmers, who stand in line every day at a
depot of the Agricultural Input Corporation (AIC) in downtown
Kathmandu these days, could receive fertilizers for their crops,
AIC officials said.
</P>
<P>
The farmers, most of them living at remote villages, have been
facing difficulties in purchasing fertilizers as the AIC's
Kathmandu depot is the only distribution site of fertilizers in
central Nepal.
</P>
<P>
Nepali farmers require some 65,000 tons of urea, 25,000 tons of
D.A.P. and 15,000 tons of potash for the cultivation of their
annual crops, sources here said.
</P>
<P>
According to an AIC official, the sharp deficit of fertilizer
supply this year was caused by several factors -- rising demand,
higher fertilizer prices in international market and the decrease
in grant assistance on fertilizers from the government.
</P>
<P>
A grant assistance of about 33 million US dollars is required
to meet the present annual demand for fertilizers in the country,
he said, adding that only less than one third of the amount has
been received in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The AIC has been purchasing fertilizers at around 250 dollars
per ton but selling at a heavily subsidized rate of more than 120
dollars, incurring heavy loss due to the inadequate government
grant assistance.
</P>
<P>
However, the demand for fertilizers would be met from next
month as 25,000 tons of fertilizers imported by the AIC have
started arriving in the country, the official said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
