<HEADLINE> New Round of U.S.-Cuba Migratory Talks Announced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Cuba and the United States are
discussing the definitive date and the venue for a new round of
negotiations on migratory matters, the Cuban Foreign Relations
Ministry announced here today.
</P>
<P>
Miguel Alfonso, spokesman for the ministry said there were
choices of venue and there was flexibility.
</P>
<P>
He said the agenda could not be changed because it dealt with
the progress of migratory agreements signed by the two countries
in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Following the last round of talks held here on December 4-5,
1996, the United States announced the return to the island of any
illegal emigrants intercepted on the high seas, or those who
entered the Guantanamo U.S. Navy base.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that an eventual Cuban request for the
extradition of Jose Fernandez Pupo, who hijacked a plane with
violence to take it to U.S. territory, would not be excluded.
</P>
<P>
Alfonso cited the case of Fernandez Pupo, who was acquitted by
a U.S. court despite his confession of the act, as more proof of
who was the main promoter and condoner of terrorism acts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
