<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Readjusting Textile Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 6 (Xinhua) -- In 1996, even though China's
textile industry lost nine billion yuan, Shanghai's textile sector
turned a profit.
</P>
<P>
The city's strategy to readjust its textile industry has shown
positive results, Vice-Mayor Jiang Yiren told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Till now, 346 local textile mills have been relocated to
cotton-producing regions in other parts of the country, while 164
went bankrupt, with 340,000 shuttles and 220,000 workers being
laid off, according to the official.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that the city's textile sector now plans to focus on
30 name-brand products, mainly fabrics for industrial use.
</P>
<P>
Local experts observed that the readjustment reflected changes
in the international market and Shanghai's textile industry will
no longer stick to only producing fabrics, but will also act as a
center for textile's import and export, design and information.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai is a major textile base in the country and the ongoing
enterprise restructuring and the booming local economy have paved
the way for the city to further develop the industry, the experts
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970606.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Antique Coins Seized From Panamanian Mayor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The authorities of the National
Institute of Culture (INAC) of Panama confiscated 189 antique
silver coins from the mayor of the city of Taboga.
</P>
<P>
The coins were found during the construction of a health center
on the island of Taboga, in the Pacific, an INAC statement said.
</P>
<P>
Taboga Mayor Carlos Esteban Chu had refused to give up the
coins, arguing that they were found in his property.
</P>
<P>
A law promulgated in 1982 stipulates that any unearthed
antiques of historical heritage should belong to the INAC.
</P>
<P>
The coins were considered to have been minted in Mexico between
1800 and 1810. On one side are the names of the Spanish sovereigns
Carlos IV and Ferdinando VII, and the other side bears the kingdom
shield bordered by the Hercules columns and the denomination of
the piece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970606.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romanian Economy Becomes Stable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The economy of Romania is
becoming stable, with inflation dropping and the foreign trade
deficit decreasing.
</P>
<P>
In the first quarter of this year, the monthly average
inflation rate amounted to an annual rate of 20.6 percent, and it
reduced to 4.5 percent in April.
</P>
<P>
The unemployment rate dropped to seven percent by May, 26,700
people less than the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Romania has taken measures to encourage exports. In March, the
country's foreign trade enjoyed, for the first time in the past
two years, a surplus of 25 million U.S. dollars. The deficit in
April also dropped to 100 million dollars, from the 400 million
dollars at the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
This year, Romania received 400 million and 550 million dollars
in loans from the International Monetary Fund and the World Bank
repectively.
</P>
<P>
The country also issued 600 million Deutsch marks (about 347
million dollars) of bonds in Europe in 1997. By June, Romania's
foreign currency reserves had reached 1.7 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
