<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Company to Set up Petrochemical Base in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 6 (Xinhua) -- BASF AG of Germany plans to set up
a petrochemical production base in Nanjing, capital of east
China's Jiangsu Province, according to a senior company official.
</P>
<P>
The base is being jointly developed by BASF, Sinochem, and the
Yangtze Petrochemical Corporation.
</P>
<P>
Sources said that the base will install a steam cracker and
other processing facilities for downstream chemical products. The
core will consist of a set of nephtha cracking facilities with a
processing capacity of 600,000 tons of ethylene a year. Other
sub-facilities involve arene and butadiene extraction, synthetic
gas production, and power plant.
</P>
<P>
The cost of the project is estimated to reach six billion
Deutsche marks.
</P>
<P>
BASF is the largest foreign investor in China's chemical
industry. With nine joint ventures in China, the company has paid
or agreed to pay one billion marks in capital.
</P>
<P>
The company has also set up three offices in China and plans to
double its sales in the country to 1.5 billion marks in the year
2000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
