<DOCNO> XIE19970606.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia's Remarkable Inflation Cure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslavia has achieved remarkable
success in controlling inflation since the country issued the
first government bond at the end of 1995.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, the total value of bonds issued by the country
amounts to 1.27 billion new dinars (about 254 million
U.S. dollars), of which, 1.1 billion dinars (about 220 million
dollars) have been sold.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia has been short of funds since the Bosnian War began
in March, 1992. The government had to issue bonds to solve the
problem, replacing the reckless issue of banknotes. This measure
stabilized the rate of new dinars to U.S. dollars at 5:1.
</P>
<P>
The first government one-month short period bond in 1997, which
totalled 50 million new dinars (about 10 million dollars), was
sold out on the Belgrade Stock Exchange following its issue on May
12. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970606.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uruguay Educates Disabled on HIV </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The Uruguayan Public Health
Ministry started an education program today to prevent the
transmission among young disabled people of the human
immunodeficiency virus (HIV) which causes AIDS.
</P>
<P>
The program will include workshops in which young deaf people
will learn about the diseases, sexual transmission
characteristics, and risks and prevention measures that had to be
adopted, said ministry authorities.
</P>
<P>
The campaign will be also directed at young blind people and
full coverage is being ensured by contacts made with national
institutions serving 4,000 blind people.
</P>
<P>
There were 2,897 people infected with the Acquired Immune
Deficiency Syndrome (AIDS) in Uruguay in 1996, and 466 deaths.
</P>
</TEXT>
