<DOCNO> XIE19970606.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Komen Steals Limelight at Golden Gala </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's Daniel Komen ran the third
fastest 5,000m of all time at the Golden Gala here on Thursday
night, stealing the limelight from Linford Christie and Frankie
Fredericks in the meet.
</P>
<P>
On a cold, wet night at the Olympic stadium, Komen surged home
in 12 minutes 48.98 seconds. The 21-year-old already has the
second best time (12:45.09) behind Ethiopian Haile Gebrselassie's
world record of 12:44.39.
</P>
<P>
Komen, who holds the 3,000m world record, was more than three
seconds clear of Moroccan hope Salah Hissou (12:52.39).
</P>
<P>
Christie, who edged Jamaican Michael Green in a photo-finish at
Hengelo last weekend, beat two men this time in another
photo-finish as the 37-year-old sprinted to victory in the 100m.
</P>
<P>
The former world and Olympic champion surged through after a
poor start, but it took a snapshot to separate him from Nigerians
Deji Aliu and Davidson Ezinwa as they hit the line in adjacent
lanes.
</P>
<P>
All three men were credited with a time of 10.20 seconds.
</P>
<P>
However, Christie failed to pull off the double in the 200m as
Fredericks, the double Olympic sprint silver medallist at Atlanta,
powered home for an unstoppable win in 20.24.
</P>
<P>
Belgian Patrick Stevens was a distant second (20.53) and
American Kevin Little third (20.60), with Christie fourth (20.67).
</P>
<P>
Russian Marina Trandenkova won the women's 200m in 22.79, ahead
of Jamaicans Merlene Frazer and Julie Cuthbert. The much heralded
showdown between Merlene Ottey and Gwen Torrence failed to
materialise.
</P>
<P>
Torrence was still in the States nursing an injury, according
to organisers, while world champion Ottey was a disappointing
sixth (23.18).  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970606.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Children Looking For Their Own Movies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Twelve-year-old Wang Chong enjoys
watching foreign cartoons on TV after school, but seldom goes to
the cinema because there are only adult films and he hasn't had a
chance to see a film about teenagers for the past three years.
</P>
<P>
Xiao Feng, a director of children's films, says that the
children's film system has strongly affected the film business. In
the early '80s, children's film producers could sell as many as
112 copies of a film nationwide, but the same films have hardly
attracted buyers since 1993.
</P>
<P>
To attract a larger audience, cinema managers prefer to show
foreign movies instead of children's films, which makes little
profit. A national survey last year showed that, among the top ten
domestic movies with high box-office receipts, children's movie
came in last.
</P>
<P>
Ozawa, a Japanese director, says that many countries face the
same problem in the children's film industry. In Japan, it's
difficult to get any backing to make children's films.
</P>
<P>
Vinold Ganatta, an Indian children's film producer, says that
India has reduced the number of children's films produced each
year from 15 to just 2.
</P>
<P>
Yu Lan, president of the Chinese Children's Film Society, says
that good movies can be educational and cultural and that Chinese
film producers should not just look for profit, but should produce
more children's films.
</P>
<P>
Dou Chunqi, head of the China Children's Film Studio (CCFS),
says that CCFS, which was founded in 1981, is China's only studio
producing films for children, and has made 224 children's movies,
accounting for a tenth of the country's total.
</P>
<P>
"The film production system has developed a lot in recent
years," Dou, said, and that scripts, camera work, artistry, and
action sequences have all improved.
</P>
<P>
He called on education departments at all levels to help get
primary and middle school students to see children's movies as a
part of their education.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970606.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Project Hope Helping Children In Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, June 6 (Xinhua) -- More than 23,000 children in
northwest China's Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region have returned to
schools, thanks to help from "Project Hope" in the last seven
years.
</P>
<P>
"Project Hope" is a nationwide aid project started in 1989
aiming to raise money for primary school children who have dropped
out of school in poverty-stricken areas.
</P>
<P>
Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region, one of the country's poorest
regions, concentrated on eight poverty-stricken counties in the
Xihaigu region, and more than eight million yuan (about one
million US dollars) was raised for the project, financing the
establishment of 75 primary schools.
</P>
<P>
With the help of the project, small libraries have established
in 240 primary schools. The project has also awarded 66 primary
schools in mountainous areas for their outstanding achievements in
developing primary school education under tough conditons.
</P>
<P>
According to official sources, the region plans to help another
60,000 school drop-outs and to set up 150 primary schools in the
next two or three years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
