<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fast-food Trays Recycling on Beijing's Top Agenda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Producers and sellers of
polystyrene food trays in Beijing are being required to collect
and recycle used and discarded trays.
</P>
<P>
This was publicized in a notice issued by the Beijing Municipal
Environmental Protection Bureau and the Beijing Industrial and
Commercial Administration early this month.
</P>
<P>
The notice requires up to 30 percent of the trays to be
recycled by 1998. The percentage should increase to 50 percent by
1999 and 60 percent by 2000, said today's "China Daily".
</P>
<P>
It also says all producers and sellers of these environmentally
unfriendly food containers should apply for registration at the
Beijing Municipal Environmental Protection Bureau before the end
of this month.
</P>
<P>
After examination and approval from both bureaux in charge of
environmental conservation and industrial and commercial
administration, producers and sellers can start their business,
the notice said.
</P>
<P>
Units and individuals are not allowed to produce or sell these
trays without permission from the bureaux.
</P>
<P>
Food trays should be retrieved at a certain percentage within
time limits or permission will be invalid.
</P>
<P>
Producers should be responsible for reducing pollution caused
by these food trays which do not decompose easily, said Zhao
Yixin, director of the Beijing Environmental Protection Bureau, at
a press conference on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
There is a grace period between the publication and
implementation dates of the notice. This allows producers to work
out plans for retrieving food trays and starting experiments.
</P>
<P>
Discarded polystyrene package materials make up three percent
to four percent of the capital's total daily garbage. It takes
years for these plastic bags, food trays and membranes for
agricultural use to decay.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
