<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Check If Figures Correctly Add Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 6 (Xinhua) -- China is to launch a nationwide
inspection this month of the implementation of the State
Statistics Law, "China Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The move, to be conducted by the State Statistics Bureau, the
Ministry of Supervision and the Legislative Affairs Bureau under
the State Council, is aimed at tackling inaccurate and even false
social and economic figures which appear in some areas.
</P>
<P>
"The move is aimed at curbing and correcting the illegal
practice of putting out incorrect economic figures, and improving
the quality of statistics," Chinese Vice-Premier Zou Jiahua was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Statistics should play a better role in decision-making, Zou
said, calling on governments and departments at all levels to pay
close attention to the inspection and take the work seriously.
</P>
<P>
The inspection should help create a sound social climate for
statistics work by spreading information about the law, he said.
</P>
<P>
China adopted the State Statistics Law in 1984 and revised it
in May last year.
</P>
<P>
"We should keep a sober mind as illegal practices which violate
the Statistics Law still exist," the vice-premier said.
</P>
<P>
Some grassroots units and officials deliberately put out false
statistics to exaggerate their achievements to paint a rosy
picture before the public and their superiors for personal reasons.
</P>
<P>
China launched two inspections on the law's implementation in
1989 and 1994 respectively.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, more than 60,000 cases involving crooked officials and
company bosses had been found breaking the law and tempering with
economic figures.
</P>
<P>
"The inspections proved successful in implementing the law,"
Zou said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970606.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuba Progresses in Environmental Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Cuba is advancing more every day
towards a sustainable development despite its enormous economic
limitations, says Ricardo Sanchez, Vice Minister of Science,
Technology, and Environment.
</P>
<P>
A bill on the environment being drafted in accordance with the
environmental problems of the island, and possible solutions, is
being given the finishing touch, Sanchez said today.
</P>
<P>
The finish of a study on the island's biological diversity,
reflecting in detail the status of the different components of the
biosphere in the Cuban archipelago, was one of the advances in the
care of nature.
</P>
<P>
He said a chapter dwelling on the role of the state and its
organs in environment and natural resources protection was added
to Article 27 of the constitution.
</P>
<P>
The constitution recognized, after the Summit of the Earth held
in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil in 1992, the linking between economic
and social development with sustainability and without detrimental
effects on the environment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
