<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hingis and Majoli Reach French Open Final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 5 (Xinhua) -- World number-one Martina Hingis and
Iva Majoli of Croatia ensured a teenage women's singles final at
the French Open after taking the semi-finals on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The 16-year-old Hingis survived an intense, big-hitting
cliffhanger against three-times champion Monica Seles and came
back after dropping the first set to record 6-7 (2/7), 7-5, 6-4
victory.
</P>
<P>
Ninth-seeded Majoli, who is three years older, ignored a severe
cold and a sleepless night to edge nervously past South Africa's
iron-willed Amanda Coetzer 6-3, 4-6, 7-5.
</P>
<P>
The two matches were complete contrasts.
</P>
<P>
Hingis and Seles, who have been there before, rose
magnificently to the occasion and kept the crowd on the edge of
their seats with a superbly dramatic encounter which could have
gone either way.
</P>
<P>
Majoli and Coetzer, bidding for a first-ever berth in a Grand
Slam final, clearly suffered stagefright -- although they, too,
kept the crowd in suspense.
</P>
<P>
Seles, the winner here in 1990, 1991 and 1992, went down with
all guns blazing against the top-seeded Hingis -- her powerful
baseline groundstrokes sometimes leaving the Swiss player looking
groggy.
</P>
<P>
But Hingis, who was unable to play any tournaments for six
weeks immediately before arriving in Paris after needing an
operation on her knee following a riding accident, still found the
space to slot a series of screaming winners which left Seles
gasping. 
</P>
</TEXT>
