<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 5 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary William
Cohen said today that Joseph Ralston remained a leading candidate
for chairman of the military Joint Chiefs of Staff despite an
adulterous affair 13 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said in a strong statement that Ralston was still among
the top candidates he was considering for the post and he would
make a recommendation to President Bill Clinton within two weeks.
</P>
<P>
"General Ralston was a leading candidate before I learned of
these events in his past and he is still a leading candidate. If I
recommend General Ralston to the president I will do so in full
confidence of his character and leadership," Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
Air Force Gen. Ralston this week disclosed to Cohen in response
to media inquiries that he had had an affair with a civilian woman
while he was a colonel and separated from his first wife 13 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued today, Ralston, vice chairman of the
joint chiefs, said he took "full responsibility for my conduct
some years ago," and thank Cohen for confidence in choosing him
despite the affair.
</P>
<P>
Ralston, 53, who was traveling in former Soviet states in
Asia, gave no indication he will withdraw as a possible candidate
to succeed Army Gen. John Shalikashvili this year. 
