<HEADLINE> Rubins: Revoking MFN to China Means to Isolate U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Revoking normal trade relations
with China would do harm to U.S. strategic interests and Isolate
the United States, Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin warned on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Rubin was making the remarks at a U.S.-China Business Council
meeting as a few lawmakers expressed their oppositions to
President Bill Clinton's decision of renewing the Most Favored
Nation (MFN) trade status for the coming year.
</P>
<P>
"Revoking normal trade relations, which some have proposed,
would fundamentally undermine our ability to advance our economic
and national security interests," he said.
</P>
<P>
"In our judgement revoking normal trade relations with China is
absolutely the wrong way," he emphasized.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said denial of the MFN trade status, the normal trade
treatment, for China would hurt U.S. consumers, undermine U.S.
interests in the Asian-Pacific region and harm efforts to promote
stability in Hong Kong after its returning to China on July 1.
</P>
<P>
"Severing trade ties with China will not isolate China. It will
isolate the United States. It will also lead other nations in Asia
to question our commitment to the region," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Revoking normal trade relations with China would also harm
Hong Kong in the name of supporting it," he continued.
</P>
<P>
Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky told reporters after
speaking to a different group that members of Congress understood
the dangers of being the only nation in the world to sever
economic ties with China.
</P>
<P>
"There is in the House a growing appreciation that to cut off
MFN is to isolate ourselves with China," Barshefsky said. "That
really is the only effect of cutting off MFN." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
