<HEADLINE> UK to Allow Divorcees to Share Pensions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 5 (Xinhua) -- British Social Security Secretary
Harriet Harman said today her government will allow divorced
couples to divide up pensions.
</P>
<P>
"I will introduce pension-sharing for divorcing couples. This
is an important step towards meeting the government's objectives
of improving the income of women in retirement," Harman said in a
written reply to the parliament.
</P>
<P>
"It is the combination of the basic state pension and a decent
second pension which prevents people from retiring into poverty.
But women are less likely than men to have a good second pension,"
she added.
</P>
<P>
The move will end the existing system whereby a divorcee can
only claim a share of an ex-partner's pension when that pension is
taken. But the new plan is unlikely to become law until the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
Harman said her proposals "will lead to fairer treatment of
pensions in financial settlements between divorcing couples and
will provide a better and more secure income in retirement for
those receiving a share of pension rights." 
</P>
</TEXT>
