<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain to Lift Rule Restricting Marriage Immigration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 5 (Xinhua) -- British government will soon lift a
immigration marriage rule which required applicants who marry
British citizens to prove they did not wed just to enter the
country.
</P>
<P>
Under the controversial "Primary Purpose Rule", foreigners
applying for entry into Britain were refused if they could not
satisfy immigration officials about their motives for marriage.
</P>
<P>
Home Secretary Jack Straw said today in a written reply to the
House of Commons that the rule will be scrapped immediately.
</P>
<P>
"Following our manifesto commitment, we are acting to end the
primary purpose rule because it is arbitrary, unfair and
ineffective and has penalized genuine, divided families and
unnecessarily increased the administrative burden on the
immigration system," he said.
</P>
<P>
But Straw said other rules on married partners applying to
enter Britain -- that the marriage was not one of convenience and
would not place a financial burden on the state -- would remain.
</P>
<P>
The rule has been criticized in Britain for the past years. The
interior ministry said the rule was ineffective and unfair and it
has placed a burden on the partners of Britons that was not placed
on other European Union nationals and should therefore be
scrapped. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
