<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Launches Training of Compliance Officers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 5 (Xinhua) -- "Compliance in Futures and Options"
the first major course created by the Futures and Options
Association (FOA) was launched at the Fourth International
Derivatives Conference here today.
</P>
<P>
The objective of the course is to develop the interpretative
and commercial reasoning of the compliance professional.
</P>
<P>
It aims to provide newcomers to the field of derivatives
compliance with a sound, broadly based understanding of the
ethical and regulatory requirements of the industry and focuses on
the acquisition of practical skills.
</P>
<P>
Compliance is the newest profession in Britain. Prior to the
advent of the Financial Services Act in 1988, most of the firms in
UK financial services would not have recognized the title
"Compliance Officer", an official from FOA said.
</P>
<P>
Ten years on, firms are recognizing that "legal and accounting
qualifications" are not in themselves enough, and there is a
growing realization that some form of training, leading in due
course to a qualification, is necessary, the official added.
</P>
<P>
The course will enable newhands to gain skills to deal with the
wide range of issues that may arise within an authorized firm
involved in both on and off-exchange derivative business.
</P>
<P>
Following the launch, Anthony Belchambers, Chief Executive of
the FOA said: "The attention given to regulators in the UK has
sometimes obscured the importance of the front-line regulator --
the Compliance Officer in firms."
</P>
<P>
"This course, created by the industry for the industry,
demonstrates the coming of age of the compliance profession and
fills an important gap in the training of those engaged in the
front line of regulation," he added.
</P>
<P>
The course will begin in September at Queens' College,
Cambridge, with candidates completing exams before Christmas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
