<DOCNO> XIE19970606.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rising US Economy Leaves Behind Many People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Although the U.S. economy is in
the strongest growth in a decade and the unemployment rate the
lowest in a quarter-century, many people were left behind and have
a hard time to find a job.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. unemployment rate has averaged 5.2 percent this year
and was down to 4.9 percent in April, the lowest since December
1973. But the good times are not good for everyone. For instance,
in the District of Columbia, the U.S. capital, the jobless rate
averaged 7.6 percent in the past four months.
</P>
<P>
Joblessness is especially higher for city dwellers than for
suburbanites, higher for teens than for adults, higher for blacks
than for whites. And, among blacks, it's significantly higher for
young men than for young women.
</P>
<P>
For whites nationally, the jobless rate average is 4.4 percent;
for blacks, 10.6 percent. For adults aged 25 to 54, it's 4.1
percent; for youth 16 to 19, 16.6 percent. For teen-age black
females, it's 27 percent; for teen-age black males, 39.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Why the big gap? Some obvious reasons are reported by U.S. new
media.
</P>
<P>
Ineffective public schools and lack of financial help for
college played a role. Unemployment rates are higher for the
youngsters with less experience and education.
</P>
<P>
Many inner-city residents in the U.S., isolated by poor public
transit systems, also find it takes too long or costs too much to
reach thriving suburbs, where sales jobs are more plentiful.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, racial discrimination persists. Black applicants
received unfavorable treatment in 20 percent of job searches
compared with 7 percent of white applicants, according to some
studies, using pairs of identically qualified black and white male
college students in Chicago and Washington.
</P>
<P>
Judging by unemployment rates, teen-age black males suffer more
from discrimination than young black women. The trend can be
partly explained by a shift away from manufacturing and blue
collar jobs toward clerical, sales and service. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970606.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Shares Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 5 (Xinhua) -- All major stock markets in Europe
ended higher today.
</P>
<P>
British shares finished higher for the first time in seven
sessions as renewed bid speculation swirled around the dealing
rooms in London's financial district. A firmer look to Wall Street
also gave the market a much needed boost. The FTSE-100, which had
dropped in the previous six trading days, ended 19.1 points up to
4,576.2.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, German shares posted minor gains amid relief that
the Bundesbank and Bonn seemed close to reconciliation in their
spat over asset revaluation, easing fears of a soft start for
monetary union. The 30-share DAX ended the bourse session up 11.19
points at 3,673.03 points.
</P>
<P>
French shares close more than two percent higher, bolstered by
relief at the composition of France's Socialist-led government.
The CAC-40 index closed up 55.48, or 2.11 percent, at 2,690.85.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
